\c 1  
\cl CHAPTER 1 
\p  
\v 1 And it was done, after that Alexan-der \sls (the son)\sls* of Philip, king of Mace-donia, which reigned first in Greece, and went out of the land of Kittim, smote Darius, king of Persians and of Medes or king of Persia and of Media, 
\p  
\v 2 he ordained many battles, and got strengths \sls (or strongholds)\sls* of \sls (or from)\sls* all; and he slew the kings of \sls (the)\sls* earth, 
\p  
\v 3 and passed forth till to the ends of \sls (the)\sls* earth, and took spoils of \sls (or from a)\sls* multitude of folks; and \sls (then)\sls* the earth was still in the sight of him. 
\p  
\v 4 And he gathered virtue, and host full strong \sls (or And he gathered a very strong army)\sls*, and the heart of him was enhanced and lift\sls (ed)\sls* up. And he got the countries of folks, and tyrants, \em either strong men\em*; and they were made to him into tribute. 
\p  
\v 5 And after these things he fell into the bed, and knew that he should die. 
\p  
\v 6 And he called his noble children \sls (or his honourable servants)\sls*, that were nourished with him from their youth, and parted to them his kingdom, when he lived yet. 
\p  
\v 7 And \sls (so)\sls* Alexander reigned twelve years, and was dead. 
\p  
\v 8 And his children wielded the realm \sls (or And his servants ruled the kingdom)\sls*, each in his place, 
\p  
\v 9 and all putted to them diadems \sls (or they all put crowns upon themselves)\sls* after his death, and the sons of them after them, \sls (for)\sls* many years; and evils were multiplied in \sls (or on the)\sls* earth. 
\p  
\v 10 And there went out of them a root of sin, Antiochus the noble \sls (or Antiochus Epiphanes)\sls*, the son of Antiochus the king, that was at Rome in hostage, and reigned in the hundred and seven and thirtieth year of the realm of \sls (the)\sls* Greeks. 
\p  
\v 11 In those days wicked sons of Israel went out, and counselled many, and said, Go we, and ordain we \add [a]\add* testa-ment \sls (or covenant)\sls* with \sls (the)\sls* heathen men, that be about us; for since we parted from them, many evils found us. 
\p  
\v 12 And the word was seen good before the eyes of them. 
\p  
\v 13 And some of the people sent, and went to the king; and he gave power to them for to do \sls (the)\sls* rightfulness of \sls (the)\sls* heathen men. 
\p  
\v 14 And they builded a school in Jerusalem, by \add [or after]\add*\sls (the)\sls* laws of \sls (the)\sls* nations; 
\p  
\v 15 and made to them prepuces \sls (or made themselves uncircumcised)\sls*, and went away from the holy testament, and were joined to \sls (the)\sls* nations, and were sold for to do evil. 
\p  
\v 16 And the realm had prosperity in the sight of Antiochus, and he began to reign in the land of Egypt, \sls (so)\sls* that he should reign on two realms. 
\p  
\v 17 And he entered into Egypt with a grievous multitude, in \sls (or with)\sls* chariots, and elephants, and horsemen, \em either knights\em*, and \add [a]\add* plenteous multitude of ships, 
\p  
\v 18 and he ordained battle against Ptolemy, king of Egypt, and Ptolemy dreaded of his face, and flew \sls (or fled)\sls*; and many were wounded, and fell down. 
\p  
\v 19 And he took the strong cities in the land of Egypt, and \add [he]\add* took the preys of the land of Egypt. 
\p  
\v 20 And Antiochus \sls (re)\sls*turned, after that he \sls (had)\sls* smote Egypt, in the hundred and three and fortieth year, and went up to Israel. And he went up to Jerusalem with a grievous multitude, 
\p  
\v 21 and entered into the hallowing \sls (or the Temple)\sls* with pride; and he took \sls (away)\sls* the golden altar, and the candle-stick of light, and all the vessels thereof, 
\p  
\v 22 and the board of proposition \sls (or the table of the showbread)\sls*, and \sls (the)\sls* vessels of floating \sls (or liquid)\sls* sacrifices, and cruets, and golden mortars, and veil, and crowns, and golden ornament that was in the face \sls (or on the front)\sls* of the temple; and he brake all. 
\p  
\v 23 And he took \sls (the)\sls* silver and \sls (the)\sls* gold, and all \sls (the)\sls* desirable vessels, and he took the privy \sls (or hidden)\sls* treasures, which he found; 
\p  
\v 24 and when he had taken up all things, he went into his land. And he made \sls (a)\sls* slaughter of men, and spake in \sls (or with)\sls* great pride. 
\p  
\v 25 And great wailing was made in Israel, and in each place of them; 
\p  
\v 26 and \sls (the)\sls* princes sorrowed inward-ly, and elder men, and \sls (the)\sls* maidens, and \sls (the)\sls* young men were made sick \sls (or feeble)\sls*, and \sls (the)\sls* fairness of women was changed. 
\p  
\v 27 Each husband took \sls (up)\sls* wailing, and they that sat in \sls (the)\sls* husband’s bed, mourned. 
\p  
\v 28 And the land was moved \sls (al)\sls*to-gether on \sls (or for the)\sls* men dwelling therein, and all the house of Jacob was clothed with confusion. 
\p  
\v 29 And after two years of days, the king sent a prince of tributes into the cities of Judea, and he came to Jerusalem with \sls (a)\sls* great company. 
\p  
\v 30 And he spake to them peaceable words in guile, and they believed to him. And suddenly he fell in on the city, and smote it with a great wound, and lost much people of Israel. 
\p  
\v 31 And he took preys of the city, and burnt it with fire, and destroyed houses thereof, and walls thereof in compass. 
\p  
\v 32 And they led \sls (the)\sls* women captive, and children, and wielded \sls (the)\sls* beasts. 
\p  
\v 33 And they builded the city of David with \add [a]\add* great wall and firm, and firm towers; and it was made to them into an high tower, \em either strength \+sls (or a stronghold)\+sls*\em*. 
\p  
\v 34 And they putted there a folk of sinners, wicked men, and they were strong in it; 
\p  
\v 35 and they putted arms, and meats \sls (or food)\sls*, and gathered \sls (the)\sls* preys of Jerusalem; and putted up there, and were made into a great snare. 
\p  
\v 36 And this thing was made into espyings in evil, \em either treasons\em*, to \sls (the)\sls* hallowing \sls (or against the Temple)\sls*, and into an evil devil in Israel evermore. 
\p  
\v 37 And they shed out innocent blood, by compass of the hallowing \sls (or all around the Temple)\sls*, and defouled the hallowing \sls (or and defiled the Temple)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 38 And \sls (the)\sls* dwellers of Jerusalem fled for them, and it was made \sls (an)\sls* habitation of strangers, and it was made strange, \em either alien\em*, to his seed, and \sls (the)\sls* sons thereof forsook it. 
\p  
\v 39 The hallowing thereof \sls (or Its Temple)\sls* was \sls (as)\sls* desolate as \sls (a)\sls* wilder-ness; \sls (the)\sls* feast days thereof were turned into mourning, \sls (the)\sls* sabbaths thereof into shame \sls (or reproof)\sls*, \sls (and the)\sls* honours thereof into nought. 
\p  
\v 40 By \add [or After]\add* the glory thereof, the evil fame thereof was multiplied, and \sls (the)\sls* highness thereof was turned into mourning. 
\p  
\v 41 And king Antiochus wrote to all his realm, that all the people should be one. 
\p  
\v 42 And they forsook each man his law; and all folks consented by \add [or after]\add* the word of king Antiochus, 
\p  
\v 43 and many of Israel consented to him, and sacrificed to idols, and defouled \sls (or defiled the)\sls* sabbath. 
\p  
\v 44 And king Antiochus sent books by the hands of messengers into Jerusalem, and into all cities of Judea, that they should pursue \sls (or follow the)\sls* laws of \sls (the)\sls* folks of \sls (the)\sls* earth, 
\p  
\v 45 and should forbid burnt sacrifices, and sacrifices, and pleasings for to be done in the temple of God, and that they should forbid the sabbath for to be hallowed, and solemn days, 
\p  
\v 46 and holy things for to be defouled \sls (or and that they should defile the Temple)\sls*, and the holy people of Israel. 
\p  
\v 47 And he commanded altars for to be builded, and temples, and idols; and swine’s flesh for to be sacrificed, and unclean beasts; 
\p  
\v 48 and for to leave their sons uncircumcised, and the souls of them for to be defouled in all uncleanness-es and abominations, 
\p  
\v 49 so that they should forget the law, and should change all the justifyings of God. 
\p  
\v 50 And \sls (that)\sls* whoever did not by the word of king Antiochus, should die. 
\p  
\v 51 By all these words he wrote to all his realm, and above-set \add [or before-set]\add* princes to the people, which should constrain these things for to be done. And they commanded to \sls (the)\sls* cities of Judea for to make sacrifice. 
\p  
\v 52 And many of the people were gathered to them, which forsook the law of the Lord, and did evils on earth. 
\p  
\v 53 And they drived \add [or drove]\add* out the people of Israel from \sls (or into)\sls* privy places, and in\sls (to)\sls* hid places of \sls (or for)\sls* fugitives, \em either fleeing men\em*. 
\p  
\v 54 In the fifteenth day of the month Kislev, \em that answereth to our November\em*, in the hundred and five and fortieth year, king Antiochus builded \sls (the)\sls* abominable idol of desolation, \em either\em*\add [or \+sls (of)\+sls*]\add*\em discomfort\em*, on the altar of God; and by all \sls (the)\sls* cities of Judea in compass they builded altars. 
\p  
\v 55 And before the gates of the houses and in streets, they burnt incenses, and sacrificed; 
\p  
\v 56 and burnt by fire the books of the law of God, and carved them \sls (up)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 57 And with whomever the books of \add [the]\add* testament of the Lord were found, and whoever kept the law of the Lord, by \add [or after]\add* the commandment of the king, they slew him. 
\p  
\v 58 In their virtue, \em either power\em*, they did these things to the people of Israel, that was found in each month in the cities. 
\p  
\v 59 And in the five and twentieth day of the month, they sacrificed on the \sls (idol)\sls* altar, that was against \sls (or on top of)\sls* the altar of God. 
\p  
\v 60 And women, that circumcised their sons, were strangled, by \add [or after]\add*\sls (the)\sls* commandment of king Antiochus; 
\p  
\v 61 and they hanged \sls (the)\sls* children by the necks, by all houses of them, and strangled them that circumcised them. 
\p  
\v 62 And many of the people of Israel determined, \em either fully deemed\em*, with-\sls (in)\sls* them\sls (selves)\sls*, that they should not eat unclean things, 
\p  
\v 63 and choosed more for to die, than for to be defouled with unclean meats. And they would not break the holy law of God, and they were slain; 
\p  
\v 64 and full great wrath was made on the people \sls (of Israel)\sls*. 
\c 2  
\cl CHAPTER 2 
\p  
\v 1 In those days Mattathias, the son of John, son of Simeon, and he \em was\em* a priest of the sons of Joarib, rose from Jerusalem, and sat in the hill Modin. 
\p  
\v 2 And he had five sons; John, \sls (that)\sls* was named Gaddis; 
\p  
\v 3 and Simon, that was named Thassis; 
\p  
\v 4 and Judas, that was called Maccabeus; 
\p  
\v 5 and Eleazar, that was named Avaran; and Jonathan, that was named Apphus. 
\p  
\v 6 These saw the evils that were done in the people of Judea and Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 7 And Mattathias said, Woe to me! whereto am I born, for to see the destroying of my people, and the defouling of the holy city, and for to sit there, when it is given into the hands of \sls (our)\sls* enemies? Holy things be made in the hand of strangers \sls (or The Temple is given into the hands of strangers)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 8 the temple thereof \sls (is)\sls* as a man unnoble; 
\p  
\v 9 \sls (the)\sls* vessels of glory thereof be led away captive. Eld \add [or Old]\add* men thereof be slain in \sls (the)\sls* streets, and young men thereof fell down by \sls (the)\sls* sword of \sls (the)\sls* enemies. 
\p  
\v 10 What folk inherited not the kingdom thereof, and wielded not \sls (the)\sls* preys thereof? 
\p  
\v 11 All \sls (the)\sls* adorning thereof is borne away; she that was free, is made the handmaiden. 
\p  
\v 12 And lo! our holy thing, and our fairness, and our clarity, is desolate, and heathen men defouled it. 
\p  
\v 13 What therefore is it to us for to live \sls (any longer)\sls*? 
\p  
\v 14 And Mattathias and his sons rent their clothes, and covered them\sls (selves)\sls* with hair-shirts, and wailed greatly. 
\p  
\v 15 And they that were sent of \sls (or by)\sls* king Antiochus, came thither, for to constrain them that fled together into the city of Modin, for to offer and burn incenses, and for to depart from the law of God. 
\p  
\v 16 And many of the people of Israel consented, and came to them; but Mat-tathias and his sons stood steadfastly. 
\p  
\v 17 And they answered, that were sent of \sls (or by)\sls* Antiochus, and said to Mat-tathias, Thou art \sls (a)\sls* prince, and most clear \sls (or glorious)\sls*, and great in this city, and adorned with sons and brethren. 
\p  
\v 18 Therefore go thou the former \sls (or the first)\sls*, and do the commandment of the king, as all folks have done, and men of Judea, and they that \sls (be)\sls* left in Jerusalem. And thou shalt be, and thy sons, among \sls (the)\sls* friends of the king, and made large in silver and gold, and many gifts. 
\p  
\v 19 And Mattathias answered, and said with \sls (a)\sls* great \sls (or a loud)\sls* voice, Though all \sls (the)\sls* folks obey to king Antiochus, \sls (so)\sls* that they go away each man from the service of the law of his fathers, and consent to his commandments, 
\p  
\v 20 I, and my sons, and my brethren shall obey to the law of our fathers. 
\p  
\v 21 God be helpful to us; it is not profitable to us for to forsake the law, and \sls (the)\sls* rightfulnesses of God. 
\p  
\v 22 We shall not hear the words of king Antiochus, neither shall make sacrifice/s \em to idols\em*, and break the commandments of our law, that we go by another way. 
\p  
\v 23 And as he ceased for to speak these words, some Jew went to, before the eyes of all men, for to sacrifice to idols on the altar, in the city of Modin, by \add [or after]\add*\sls (the)\sls* commandment of the king. 
\p  
\v 24 And Mattathias saw, and sorrowed, and his reins trembled together, and his madness, \em that is, great wrath by \+sls (his)\+sls* fervent love\em*, was kindled by \add [or after]\add*\sls (the)\sls* doom of the law; and he leaped in, and slew him on the altar. 
\p  
\v 25 But and \sls (or also)\sls* he slew in that time the man whom king Antiochus sent, which compelled \sls (them)\sls* for to offer, and he destroyed the altar. 
\p  
\v 26 And he loved fervently the law, as Phinehas did to Zimri, son of Salu. 
\p  
\v 27 And Mattathias cried with \sls (a)\sls* great \sls (or a loud)\sls* voice in the city, and said, Each man that hath fervent love of \sls (or for)\sls* the law, ordain a testament, \em that is, a covenant\em*, and go he out after me. 
\p  
\v 28 And he flew \sls (or fled)\sls*, and his sons, into \sls (the)\sls* mountains, and left whatever things they had in the city. 
\p  
\v 29 Then many seeking doom and rightwiseness, went down into \sls (the)\sls* desert, that they should sit there, 
\p  
\v 30 they and the sons of them, and \sls (the)\sls* women of them, and \sls (the)\sls* beasts of them; for evils were hard on them. 
\p  
\v 31 And it was told to men of the king, and to the host, that were in Jerusalem, \add [in]\add* the city of David, that some men went away, that destroyed the commandment of the king, into privy places in \sls (the)\sls* desert; and many had gone after them. 
\p  
\v 32 And anon \sls (or at once)\sls* they went to \sls (or after)\sls* them, and ordained against them battle, in the day of sabbaths; 
\p  
\v 33 and said to them, Against-stand ye also now yet? go ye out, and do after the word of king Antiochus, and ye shall live. 
\p  
\v 34 And they said, We shall not go out, neither \add [we]\add* shall do the word of the king, that we defoul the day of sabbaths. 
\p  
\v 35 And they stirred battle against them. 
\p  
\v 36 And they answered not to them, neither threw a stone to \sls (or at)\sls* them, neither stopped privy places, 
\p  
\v 37 and said, Die we all in our simple-ness \sls (or our innocence)\sls*, and heaven and earth shall be witnesses on \sls (or for)\sls* us, that unjustly ye lose \sls (or destroy)\sls* us. 
\p  
\v 38 And they gave to them battle in \sls (or on the)\sls* sabbaths, and they were dead, and \sls (the)\sls* wives of them, and \sls (the)\sls* sons of them, and \sls (the)\sls* beasts of them, till to a thousand persons of men. 
\p  
\v 39 And Mattathias knew, and his friends; and they had mourning on them greatly. 
\p  
\v 40 And a man said to his neighbor, If we all shall do as our brethren did, and shall not fight against \sls (the)\sls* heathen men, for our lives, and our justifyings, the sooner they shall destroy us from \sls (off)\sls* the earth. 
\p  
\v 41 And they thought in that day, and said, Each man whoever cometh to us in battle, in the day of sabbaths, fight we against him, and die we not all, as our brethren be dead in privy places. 
\p  
\v 42 Then the synagogue of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, strong in mights of Israel, was gathered to them. Every willful \sls (or willing)\sls* man in the law, 
\p  
\v 43 and all that fled from evils, were added to them, and they were made to them to steadfastness. 
\p  
\v 44 And they gathered an host, and smited sinners in their wrath, and wicked men in their indignation; and the others fled to nations, for to escape. 
\p  
\v 45 And Mattathias environed, and his friends, and destroyed \sls (the)\sls* altars, 
\p  
\v 46 and circumcised children uncir-cumcised, how many ever they found in the coasts of Israel, in strength. 
\p  
\v 47 And they pursued the sons of pride, and the work had prosperity in their hands. 
\p  
\v 48 And they got the law from \sls (or out of)\sls* the hands of \sls (the)\sls* heathen men, and from \sls (or out of)\sls* the hands of kings, and gave not strength to the sinner. 
\p  
\v 49 And \sls (the)\sls* days of Mattathias of \sls (or for)\sls* dying nighed, and he said to his sons, Now pride is comforted, and chastising, and time of destruction, and the wrath of indignation. 
\p  
\v 50 Now therefore, sons, be ye pur-suers, \em either lovers\em*, of the law, and give ye your lives for the testament \sls (or the covenant)\sls* of \sls (our)\sls* fathers. 
\p  
\v 51 And bethink ye on the works of \sls (our)\sls* fathers, which they did in their generations, and ye shall receive great glory, and \sls (an)\sls* everlasting name. 
\p  
\v 52 Whether in temptation Abraham was not found true, \em either faithful\em*, and it was areckoned to him to rightwiseness? 
\p  
\v 53 Joseph, in \sls (the)\sls* time of his anguish, kept \sls (the)\sls* commandment, and was made lord of Egypt. 
\p  
\v 54 Phinehas, our father, in fervently loving the fervent love of God, took testament \sls (or received the covenant)\sls* of \sls (an)\sls* everlasting priesthood. 
\p  
\v 55 Jesus, \em either Joshua\em*, while he \add [ful]\add* filled the word, was made \sls (a)\sls* duke in Israel. 
\p  
\v 56 Caleb, while he witnessed in the church \sls (or before the congregation)\sls*, took heritage \sls (or received the inheritance)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 57 David, in \sls (or for)\sls* his mercy, got the seat of \sls (the)\sls* kingdom, into worlds. 
\p  
\v 58 Elijah, while he fervently loved the fervent love of the law, was received into heaven. 
\p  
\v 59 Hananiah, Azariah, and Mishael, believed, and were delivered from the flame. 
\p  
\v 60 Daniel, in his simpleness \sls (or his integrity)\sls*, was delivered from the mouth of lions. 
\p  
\v 61 And thus bethink ye by generation and generation, for all that hope into him be not made unsteadfast. 
\p  
\v 62 And dread ye not of the words of a man a sinner, for the glory of him is turd\sls (s)\sls* and worm\sls (s)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 63 today he is enhanced \sls (or is exalted)\sls*, and tomorrow he shall not be found, for he is \sls (re)\sls*turned into his earth, and his thought shall perish. 
\p  
\v 64 Therefore, ye sons, be comforted \sls (or strengthened)\sls*, and do ye manly in the law; for when ye shall do those things that be bidden to you in the law of your Lord God, in it ye shall be glorious. 
\p  
\v 65 And lo! Simon, your brother; I know, that he is a man of counsel, hear ye him evermore, and he shall be \sls (a)\sls* father to you. 
\p  
\v 66 And Judas Maccabeus, strong in mights from his youth, be to you a prince in \add [or of]\add*\sls (the)\sls* knighthood, and he shall do \sls (the)\sls* battle of \sls (or for)\sls* the people. 
\p  
\v 67 And ye shall bring to you all \sls (the)\sls* doers of the law, and avenge ye the vengeance of your people. 
\p  
\v 68 Yield ye yielding to \sls (the)\sls* heathen men, and take ye attention to the behest\sls (s)\sls*, \sls (or commandments,)\sls* of the law. 
\p  
\v 69 And he blessed them, and was put to his fathers. 
\p  
\v 70 And he was dead in the hundred and six and fortieth year, and was buried of \sls (or by)\sls* his sons into \sls (the)\sls* sepulchre of his fathers in Modin; and all Israel wailed him with great wailing. 
\c 3  
\cl CHAPTER 3 
\p  
\v 1 And Judas, that was called Maccabeus, the son of Mattathias, rose \sls (up)\sls* for him. 
\p  
\v 2 And all his brethren helped him, and all that joined them\sls (selves)\sls* to his father, and they fought the battle of Israel with gladness. 
\p  
\v 3 And he alarged \sls (or enlarged)\sls* glory to his people, and clothed him\sls (self)\sls* with an habergeon as a giant, and girt him\sls (self)\sls* with his armours of battle in battles, and defended castles \sls (or the host, or his army)\sls* with his sword. 
\p  
\v 4 He was made like a lion in his works, and as a whelp of a lion roaring in his hunting. 
\p  
\v 5 And he pursued wicked men, and sought them \sls (out)\sls*; and he burnt them in flames, that disturbed, or troubled, his people. 
\p  
\v 6 And his enemies were put aback for dread of him, and all workers of wick-edness were troubled \sls (al)\sls*together; and health was \sls (ad)\sls*dressed in his hand \sls (or deliverance was directed by his hand)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 7 And he wrathed many kings, and gladded Jacob, \em that is, the people of Israel\em*, in his works, and into \sls (the)\sls* world his mind \sls (or memory)\sls*\em is\em* in blessing. 
\p  
\v 8 And he went through the cities of Judea, and lost unpious men of them, and turned away wrath from Israel. 
\p  
\v 9 And he was named till to the utmost of \sls (the)\sls* earth, and he gathered men perishing. 
\p  
\v 10 And Apollonius gathered \sls (the)\sls* folks, and from Samaria much virtue, and great, \sls (or a very great host, or army)\sls*, for to fight against Israel. 
\p  
\v 11 And Judas knew, and went out against him, and smote, and slew him. And many wounded fell down, and the others fled; 
\p  
\v 12 and he took \sls (the)\sls* preys of them. And Judas took away the sword of Apollonius, and was fighting there-with in all \sls (his)\sls* days. 
\p  
\v 13 And Seron, \sls (a)\sls* prince of the host of Syria, heard, that Judas gathered a gathering, and the church \sls (or the con-gregation)\sls* of faithful men with him. 
\p  
\v 14 And he said, I shall make to me a name, and I shall be glorified in the realm, and I shall overcome Judas, and them that be with him, which despised the king’s word. 
\p  
\v 15 And he made ready him\sls (self)\sls*; and the castles \sls (or the host)\sls* of unpious men, strong helpers, went up with him, for to do vengeance on the sons of Israel. 
\p  
\v 16 And they nighed unto Bethhoron; and Judas went out against them, with \sls (a)\sls* few men. 
\p  
\v 17 Forsooth as they saw the host coming to them in meeting, they said to Judas, How may we few fight against so great \sls (a)\sls* multitude, so strong; and we be made weary by fasting this day? 
\p  
