\v 26 and that many of them were taken \add [or caught]\add* in Bozrah, and Bosor, and in Alema, and in Casphor, and Maked, and Carnaim; all these \em were\em* strong cities and great. 
\p  
\v 27 But and in other cities of Gilead they be holden caught. And on the mor-row they ordained for to move the host to those cities, and for to take \sls (them)\sls*, and \sls (to)\sls* do away them in one day. 
\p  
\v 28 And Judas turned, and his host, the way into \sls (the)\sls* desert of Bozrah suddenly; and \add [he]\add* occupied the city, and slew each male by the sharpness of \sls (the)\sls* sword, and took all the spoils of them, and burnt it with fire. 
\p  
\v 29 And they rose thence in \sls (the)\sls* night, and went unto the strengthening. 
\p  
\v 30 And it was made in \sls (the)\sls* springing of \sls (the)\sls* day, when they raised \sls (up)\sls* their eyes, and lo! much people, of whom was no number, bearing ladders and engines, for to take the strengthening \sls (or the stronghold)\sls*, and overcome them. 
\p  
\v 31 And Judas saw, that battle began, and cry of battle ascended into heaven, as \add [a]\add* trump, and great cry of \add [a]\add* city. 
\p  
\v 32 And he said to his host, Fight ye today for your brethren. 
\p  
\v 33 And he came, and three orders after them \add [or And he came in three orders after them]\add*, and they cried with trumps, and cried in prayer. 
\p  
\v 34 And \sls (the)\sls* hosts of Timothy \sls (or of Timotheus)\sls* knew, that it was Macca-beus, and they fled from his face. And they have smitten them with \sls (a)\sls* great wound; and there fell down of them in that day almost eight thousand of men. 
\p  
\v 35 And Judas turned away into Miz-peh; and \add [he]\add* overcame \sls (it)\sls*, and took it, and slew each male thereof, and took \sls (the)\sls* spoils of it, and burnt it with fire. 
\p  
\v 36 From thence he went, and took Casphor, and Maked, and Bosor, and other cities of Gilead. 
\p  
\v 37 Forsooth after these words, Timothy gathered another host, and putted tents against Raphon, over the stream. 
\p  
\v 38 And Judas sent for to behold the host, and they told again to him, and said, That all \sls (the)\sls* heathen men that be in our compass, full much host, came together to him. 
\p  
\v 39 And they hired Arabians into help to \sls (or for)\sls* them, and they have set \sls (up their)\sls* tents over the stream, \em and be\em* ready for to come to thee into battle. And Judas went against \sls (or towards)\sls* them. 
\p  
\v 40 And Timothy said to the princes of his host, When Judas nigheth, and his host, to the stream of water, if he passeth former \sls (or over first)\sls* to us, we shall not be able to abide him, for he mighty shall be able to be against us. 
\p  
\v 41 Soothly if he dreadeth for to pass \sls (over)\sls*, and setteth \sls (up his)\sls* tents beyond the flood \sls (or river)\sls*, pass we over to them, and we shall be able to be against him. 
\p  
\v 42 Forsooth as Judas nighed to the stream of water, he ordained scribes, \em either writers\em*, of the people, beside the stream, and commanded to them, and said, Leave ye none of \sls (the)\sls* men, but come all into \sls (the)\sls* battle. 
\p  
\v 43 And he the former \sls (or first)\sls* passed over to them, and all the people after him. And all these heathen men were all-broken from the face of them, and they casted away their arms; and they fled to the temple, that was at Carnaim. 
\p  
\v 44 And \em Judas\em* occupied that city, and burnt the temple with fire, and all that were in it; and Carnaim was oppress-ed, and might not abide \add [or sustain]\add* against the face of Judas. 
\p  
\v 45 And Judas gathered all Israelites that were in Gilead, from the least to the most, and wives of them, and children, and a full great host, that they should come into the land of Judea. 
\p  
\v 46 And they came till to Ephron, and this great city, put in the entry, \em was\em* full strong; and there was not for to bow away from it, in \sls (the)\sls* right half or left, but the way was through the middle. 
\p  
\v 47 And they that were in the city closed in them\sls (selves)\sls*, and stopped \sls (up)\sls* the gates with stones. 
\p  
\v 48 And Judas sent to them with peace-able words, and said, Pass we by your land, for to go into our land, and no man shall annoy \sls (or shall harm)\sls* you, only on feet we shall go. And they would not open to them. 
\p  
\v 49 And Judas commanded for to preach in \sls (the)\sls* tents, \em either \+sls (the)\+sls* host\em*, that each man should apply, \sls (or encamp at)\sls*, in what place he was. 
\p  
\v 50 And \sls (the)\sls* men of virtue applied them \sls (or And the fighting men encamp-ed themselves)\sls*, and he fought against that city all day and all night, and the city was betaken in\sls (to)\sls* his hand\sls (s)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 51 And they slew each male by the sharpness of \sls (the)\sls* sword, and drew up by the roots it \add [or drew it up by the roots]\add*, and took the spoils thereof, and passed by all the city on the slain men. 
\p  
\v 52 And they passed over \sls (the)\sls* Jordan, in the great field against the face of \sls (or opposite)\sls* Bethshan. 
\p  
\v 53 And Judas was gathering the last men, and admonished the people by all the way, till they came into the land of Judea. 
\p  
\v 54 And they went up into the hill of Zion with gladness and joy, and offered burnt sacrifices, that no man of them fell down, \em or was dead\em*, till they \sls (re)\sls*turned again in peace. 
\p  
\v 55 And in the days in which Judas was, and Jonathan, in the land of Gilead, and Simon, his brother, in Galilee, against the face of Ptolemais, 
\p  
\v 56 Joseph, son of Zechariah, heard, and Azariah, prince of virtue \sls (or the leaders of the hosts)\sls*, the things done well, and \sls (the)\sls* battles that were made. 
\p  
\v 57 And he said, Make we also a name to us, and go we for to fight against heathen men, that be in our compass. 
\p  
\v 58 And he commanded to these that were in his host, and they went forth to Jamnia. 
\p  
\v 59 And Gorgias went out of the city, and his men, against them, into fight. 
\p  
\v 60 And Joseph and Azariah were driven into, or unto, the ends of Judea; and there fell down in that day of the people of Israel, men to two thousands. 
\p  
\v 61 And a great wound was made in the people; for they heard not Judas and his brethren, and guessed them-\sls (selves)\sls* to do \sls (something)\sls* strongly. 
\p  
\v 62 Forsooth they were not of \sls (or from)\sls* the seed of those men, by which health \sls (or deliverance)\sls* was made in Israel. 
\p  
\v 63 And \sls (the)\sls* men of Juda\sls (s)\sls* were magnified greatly in the sight of all Israel \sls (or And Judas and his men were greatly magnified in the sight of all Israel)\sls*, and of all \sls (the)\sls* heathen men, where the name of them was heard. 
\p  
\v 64 And they came together, crying to them prosperity, \em either praisings\em*. 
\p  
\v 65 And Judas went out, and his brethren, and overcame the sons of Esau, in the land that is at the south; and he smote Hebron, and \sls (the)\sls* villages thereof, and destroyed the wardings, or the walls, thereof, and burnt with fire \sls (the)\sls* towers thereof in compass. 
\p  
\v 66 And he moved \sls (the)\sls* tents, for to go into the land of \sls (the)\sls* aliens; and went through Samaria. 
\p  
\v 67 In that day \sls (some)\sls* priests fell down in battle, while they would \sls (or desired to)\sls* do strongly, while \sls (or for)\sls* without counsel they went out into battle. 
\p  
\v 68 And Judas bowed away \sls (or turned)\sls* into Azotus, in the land of \sls (the)\sls* aliens, and destroyed \sls (the)\sls* altars of them, and burnt in fire the spoils of their gods, and took \sls (the)\sls* preys of \sls (the)\sls* cities; and \sls (then)\sls*\sls (re)\sls*turned again into the land of Judea. 
\c 6  
\cl CHAPTER 6 
\p  
\v 1 And king Antiochus walked through the high countries, and heard that a city, Elymais, was in Persia, the noblest and \sls (most)\sls* plenteous in silver and gold; 
\p  
\v 2 and a temple in it \em was\em* full rich \sls (or and in it \+em was\+em* a very rich temple)\sls*, and there \em were\em* golden veils, and haber-geons, and shields, which Alexander \sls (the son)\sls* of Philip, king of Macedonia, left, that reigned the first in Greece. 
\p  
\v 3 And he came, and sought for to take the city, and \sls (to)\sls* rob it; and he might not, for the word was known to them that were in the city. 
\p  
\v 4 And they rised up into battle, and he flew from thence, and went away with great heaviness, and \sls (re)\sls*turned again to Babylon. 
\p  
\v 5 And there came \em one\em*, that told to him in Persia, that the hosts that were in the land of Judea were driven \sls (away)\sls*, 
\p  
\v 6 and that Lysias went with strong virtue in \sls (or with the great power of)\sls* the first, \em or \+sls (the)\+sls* best\em*, men, and was driven \sls (away)\sls* from the face of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, and \sls (that)\sls* they waxed strong in arms, and strengths \sls (or strongholds)\sls*, and many preys, which they took of tents, \em either \+sls (the)\+sls* hosts\em*, that they slew; 
\p  
\v 7 and that they destroyed the abomination, which he builded on the altar that was in Jerusalem, and they \sls (en)\sls*compassed with high walls the hallowing \sls (or the Temple)\sls*, as before, but and Bethsura, his city. 
\p  
\v 8 And it was done, as the king heard these words, he dreaded, and was moved greatly, and fell down into a bed, and fell into a great sickness for heaviness, for it was not done as he thought. 
\p  
\v 9 And he was there many days, for great heaviness was renewed in him, and he deemed himself for to die. 
\p  
\v 10 And he called all his friends, and said to them, Sleep passed away from mine eyes, and I failed in heart, and fell down for busyness \add [or I fell down in heart for busyness]\add*; 
\p  
\v 11 and I said in mine heart, Into how great tribulation became I \add [or came I]\add*, and into what waves of heaviness in which I am now, that was merry, and beloved in my power? 
\p  
\v 12 Now forsooth I bethink on the evils that I did to Jerusalem, from whence and I took all \sls (the)\sls* golden spoils, and silvern, that were therein; and I sent without cause, that men dwelling in Judea to be done away. 
\p  
\v 13 Therefore I knew that these evils found me therefore, and lo! I perish by great heaviness in an alien land. 
\p  
\v 14 And he called \sls (for)\sls* Philip, one of his friends, and made him sovereign on all his realm; 
\p  
\v 15 and gave to him a diadem, and his stole, and ring, for to lead Antiochus, his son, and nourish him \sls (up)\sls*, \sls (or to nurse him)\sls*, and that he should reign. 
\p  
\v 16 And king Antiochus died there, in the hundred and nine and fortieth year. 
\p  
\v 17 And Lysias knew, that the king was dead, and \add [he]\add* ordained Antiochus, the son of him, for to reign, whom he nourished \sls (or nursed, when he was)\sls* young; and \add [he]\add* called his name Eupator. 
\p  
\v 18 And they that were in the high tower, closed \sls (up)\sls*\sls (al)\sls*together Israel in compass of holy things \sls (or the Temple)\sls*, and sought to them evils evermore, to \sls (the)\sls* strengthening of heathen men. 
\p  
\v 19 And Judas thought for to destroy them, and called together all the people, for to besiege them. 
\p  
\v 20 And they came together, and besieged them, in the hundred and fiftieth year; and they made arblasts \sls (or arrow-blasters)\sls*, \em that is, an instrument for to cast shafts, and stones\em*, and engines. 
\p  
\v 21 And some of them that were besieged, went out; and some unfaithful \add [or unpious]\add* men of Israel joined themselves to them, 
\p  
\v 22 and went to the king, and said, How long doest thou not doom, and avengest not our brethren? 
\p  
\v 23 And we deemed for to serve thy father, and for to walk in his behests, and obey to his commandments. 
\p  
\v 24 And the sons of our people aliened \sls (or alienated)\sls* them\sls (selves)\sls* from us for this thing; and whichever \sls (or whom-ever)\sls* were found of us, were slain, and our heritages were ravished away. 
\p  
\v 25 And not only to us they stretched out the hand, but and into all our coasts. 
\p  
\v 26 And lo! they applied today to \sls (or encamped at)\sls* the high tower in Jerusalem, for to occupy it, and they strengthened a strengthening \sls (or stronghold)\sls* in Bethsura. 
\p  
\v 27 And if thou shalt not before come them more swiftly, they shall do greater things than these, and thou shalt not be able to wield them. 
\p  
\v 28 And the king was wroth, as he heard this thing, and called together all his friends, and princes of his host, and them that were over \sls (the)\sls* horsemen; 
\p  
\v 29 but also an hired host from other realms, and \sls (the)\sls* isles, and \sls (the)\sls* coasts came to him. 
\p  
\v 30 And the number of his host was an hundred thousand of footmen, and twenty thousand of horsemen, and two and thirty elephants taught to battle. 
\p  
\v 31 And they came by Idumea \sls (or through Edom)\sls*, and they applied to \sls (or encamped at)\sls* Bethsura, and fought \sls (for)\sls* many days; and they made en-gines, and they went out, and burnt them in \sls (or with)\sls* fire, and fought manly. 
\p  
\v 32 And Judas went from the high tower, and moved tents to Bethzech-ariah, against \sls (the)\sls* tents of the king. 
\p  
\v 33 And the king rose before the light, and stirred the host into fierceness, against \sls (or towards)\sls* the way of Beth-zechariah; and the hosts made ready them\sls (selves)\sls*\sls (al)\sls*together into \sls (or for)\sls* battle, and sang in \sls (or with)\sls* trumps. 
\p  
\v 34 And to \sls (the)\sls* elephants they showed \sls (the)\sls* blood of grape\sls (s)\sls*, and \sls (of)\sls* morus, \em or \+sls (of)\+sls* mulberry trees\em*, for to whet them into battle. 
\p  
\v 35 And they parted the beasts by \sls (or among the)\sls* legions; and to each elephant a thousand men stood nigh in habergeons chained, \em or mailed\em*, together, and brazen helmets in \sls (or on)\sls* their heads, and five hundred horse-men chosen \add [or chosen horsemen]\add* were ordained to \sls (or for)\sls* each beast. 
\p  
\v 36 These were there before the time, wherever the beast was; and whither ever it went, they went, and departed not therefrom. 
\p  
\v 37 But and firm towers of tree \sls (or of wood)\sls*\em were\em* on them, defending by all the beasts, and on them \em were\em* engines, and on each by themselves men of virtue \sls (or strong men)\sls* two and thirty, which fought from above, and within \em was\em* the master of the beast. 
\p  
\v 38 And he ordained the residue multitude of \sls (the)\sls* horsemen on this half and \sls (on)\sls* that half, into two parts, for to move \sls (al)\sls*together the host with \sls (the)\sls* trumps, and for to constrain the men made thick in their legions. 
\p  
\v 39 And as the sun shined into \sls (or onto)\sls* the golden shields, and brazen, the hills shined again of \sls (or from)\sls* them, and shined again, as lamps of fire. 
\p  
\v 40 And a part of the king’s host was parted by \sls (or to the)\sls* high hills, and other\sls (s)\sls* by \sls (or to the)\sls* low places; and they went warily, and ordinately. 
\p  
\v 41 And all men dwelling in the land were moved \sls (al)\sls*together of \sls (or by)\sls* the voice of \sls (the)\sls* multitude of them, and \sls (the)\sls* in-going of \sls (the)\sls* company, and \sls (the)\sls* hurtling together of \sls (the)\sls* armours; for the host was full great and strong. 
\p  
\v 42 And Judas and his host nighed into battle; and there fell down of the king’s host six hundred men. 
\p  
\v 43 And Eleazar, the son of Avaran, saw one of the beasts habergeoned with habergeons of the king, and it was high standing over \sls (the)\sls* other beasts; and it was seen to him \sls (or it seemed to him)\sls*, that the king was on it. 
\p  
\v 44 And he gave himself for to deliver his people, \sls (and)\sls* for to get to him\sls (self)\sls* a name everlasting. 
\p  
\v 45 And he ran thereto hardily, into the middle of \sls (the)\sls* legion, and killed on the right half and on the left; and they fell down from him hither and thither. 
\p  
\v 46 And he went under the feet of the elephant, and under-putted himself thereto, and slew it; and it fell down into \sls (or onto the)\sls* earth on him, and he was dead there. 
\p  
\v 47 And they saw the virtue \sls (or the strength)\sls* of the king, and the fierceness of his host, and turned away them-selves from them. 
\p  
\v 48 Forsooth \sls (the)\sls* tents \sls (or the host)\sls* of the king went up against them, into Jerusalem; and \sls (the)\sls* tents of the king applied to Judea, and to the hill of Zion \sls (or the king pitched his tents before or towards Judea, and mount Zion)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 49 and he made peace with these that were in Bethsura. And they went out of the city, for foods were not to them closed \sls (up)\sls*\sls (al)\sls*together there, for the sabbaths of \sls (the)\sls* earth were. 
\p  
\v 50 And the king took Bethsura, and ordained there \sls (a)\sls* keeping, for to keep it. 
\p  
\v 51 And he turned the tents to the place of hallowing \sls (for)\sls* many days \sls (or And he turned the host, to besiege the Temple for many days)\sls*; and ordained there arblasts \sls (or arrow-blasters)\sls*, and engines, and darts, \em or castings\em*, of fire, and torments for to cast stones and darts, and scorpions for to shoot arrows, and slings. 
\p  
\v 52 Forsooth and they made engines against the engines of them, and \add [they]\add* fought \sls (for)\sls* many days. 
\p  
\v 53 Forsooth meats were not in the city, for that it was the seventh year; and they that \sls (were)\sls* left of \sls (the)\sls* heathen men in Judea, had wasted the reliefs \sls (or had eaten the remnants)\sls* of those things that were kept. 
\p  
\v 54 And few men left in holy things \sls (or And there were only a few men left in the Temple)\sls*, for hunger had taken them; and they were scattered, each man into his \sls (own)\sls* place. 
\p  
\v 55 And Lysias heard, that Philip, whom king Antiochus ordained, when he lived yet, that he should nourish \sls (up)\sls* Antiochus, his son, \sls (so)\sls* that he should reign, 
\p  
\v 56 \sls (re)\sls*turned again from Persia and Media, and the host that went with him. And that he seeketh for to take the causes of the realm, 
\p  
\v 57 \em Lysias\em* hast\sls (en)\sls*ed for to go, and said to the king, and \sls (the)\sls* dukes of the host, We fail each day, and little meat \sls (or food)\sls* is \sls (left)\sls* to \sls (or for)\sls* us, and the place which we besiege, is strong, and it falleth to us for to ordain of the realm. 
\p  
\v 58 Therefore now give we right hands to these men, and make we peace with them, and with all the folk of them; 
\p  
\v 59 and ordain we to them, \sls (so)\sls* that they go in lawful things as before; for why for the lawful things of them which we despised, they be wroth, and have done all these things. 
\p  
\v 60 And the word pleased in the sight of the king, and of \sls (the)\sls* princes; and he sent to them for to make peace, and they received it. 
\p  
\v 61 And the king swore to them, and \sls (the)\sls* princes; and they went out of the strengthening \sls (or the stronghold)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 62 And the king entered into the mount Zion, and he saw the strength-ening of the place; and he brake full soon the oath that he swore, and commanded for to destroy the wall in compass. 
\p  
\v 63 And he departed away hastily, and \sls (re)\sls*turned again to Antioch, and found Philip reigning in the city; and he fought against him, and occupied the city by strength. 
\c 7  
\cl CHAPTER 7 
\p  
\v 1 In the hundred year and one and fifty, Demetrius, son of Seleucus, went out from the city of Rome, and went up with a few men into a city nigh the sea, and reigned there. 
\p  
\v 2 And it was done, as he entered into the house of the realm of his fathers, the host caught Antiochus, and Lysias, for to bring them to him. 
\p  
\v 3 And the thing was known to him, and he said, Do not ye show to me the face\sls (s)\sls* of them. 
\p  
\v 4 And the host slew them. And Demetrius sat on the seat of his realm; 
\p  
\v 5 and wicked men and unfaithful of Israel came to him, and Alcimus, duke of them, that would be made \sls (the high)\sls* priest; 
\p  
\v 6 and accused the people with the king, and said, Judas and his brethren lost \sls (all)\sls* thy friends, and diversely lost \sls (or drove)\sls*\add [or scattered]\add* us from our land. 
\p  
\v 7 Now therefore send thou a man, to whom thou believest, that he go, and see all the destroying that he hath done to us, and to \sls (the)\sls* countries of the king; and \sls (then)\sls* he punish all \sls (the)\sls* friends of him, and \sls (the)\sls* helpers of them. 
\p  
\v 8 And the king chose of his friends Bacchides, that was lord over the great flood \sls (or beyond the Euphrates River)\sls* in the realm, and true to the king, 
\p  
\v 9 and \add [he]\add* sent him, for to see the destroying that Judas did; and he ordained unfaithful Alcimus into \sls (the)\sls* priesthood, and bade him \sls (to)\sls* do vengeance on the sons of Israel. 
\p  
\v 10 And they rose, and came with \sls (a)\sls* great host into the land of Judea; and they sent messengers, and spake to Judas and his brethren, with peace-able words in guile. 
\p  
\v 11 And they gave not attention to their words; for they saw, that they came with \sls (a)\sls* great host. 
\p  
\v 12 And the congregation of scribes came together to Alcimus and Bacchides, for to ask \sls (for)\sls* those things that be just; 
\p  
\v 13 and the first \sls (were the)\sls* Hasideans, that were among the sons of Israel, and they asked of them \sls (for)\sls* peace. 
\p  
\v 14 For they said, A man, \sls (a)\sls* priest of the seed of Aaron, cometh, \sls (and)\sls* he shall not deceive us. 
\p  
\v 15 And he spake with them peace-able words, and swore to them, and said, We shall not bring into you evils, neither to your friends. 
\p  
\v 16 And they believed to him. And \sls (then)\sls* he caught of them sixty men, and slew them in one day, by \add [or after]\add* the word that is written, 
\p  
\v 17 They shed out the fleshes of thy saints, and \sls (the)\sls* blood of them in compass of Jerusalem, and there was not that buried \sls (them)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 18 And dread and trembling fell into all the people, for they said, There is not truth and doom in them; for they have broken the statute, \em or ordinance\em*, and the oath that they swore. 
\p  
\v 19 And Bacchides moved tents from Jerusalem, and applied into \sls (or pitched at)\sls* Bethzaith; and sent \sls (for)\sls*, and caught many of them that fled from him; and he killed some of the people, and casted \sls (them)\sls* into a great pit. 
\p  
\v 20 And he betook the country to Alcimus, and left with him help, into \sls (the)\sls* helping of him. And Bacchides went to the king, 
\p  
\v 21 and Alcimus did enough, for the princehood of his priesthood. 
\p  
\v 22 And all came together to him, which disturbed, or troubled, their people, and wielded the land of Judea; and \add [they]\add* did great vengeance in Israel. 
\p  
\v 23 And Judas saw all the evils, that Alcimus did, and they that were with him, to the sons of Israel, much more than \sls (the)\sls* heathen men. 
\p  
\v 24 And he went out into all the coasts of Judea in compass, and did venge-ance on men forsakers, and they ceased for to go out further into the country. 
\p  
\v 25 Forsooth Alcimus saw, that Judas had \sls (the)\sls* victory, and they that were with him; and he knew that he may not \sls (or he was not able to)\sls* abide them, and he went again to the king, and accused them in \sls (or of)\sls* many sins. 
\p  
\v 26 And the king sent Nicanor, one of his nobler princes, that was haunting enmities against Israel, and command-ed him for to destroy the people. 
\p  
\v 27 And Nicanor came into Jerusalem, with \sls (a)\sls* great host, and he sent to Judas and his brethren with guile, by peaceable words, saying, 
\p  
\v 28 Fight be not betwixt me and you; I shall come with \sls (a)\sls* few men, for to see your faces with peace. 
\p  
\v 29 And he came to Judas, and they greeted them\sls (selves)\sls* together peace-ably; and \sls (the)\sls* enemies were ready for to ravish \sls (or to kidnap)\sls* Judas. 
\p  
\v 30 And the word was known to Judas, that with guile he came to him; and he was afeared of him, and he would no more see his face. 
\p  
\v 31 And Nicanor knew, that his coun-sel was known, and he went out against Judas into fight, beside Capharsalama. 
\p  
\v 32 And there fell down of Nicanor’s host almost five thousand men, and they fled into the city of David. 
\p  
\v 33 And after these words Nicanor went up into the hill of Zion, and there went out of \sls (the Temple some)\sls* priests of the people, for to greet him in peace, and for to show to him \sls (the)\sls* burnt sacri-fices, that were offered for the king. 
\p  
\v 34 And he scorned and despised them, and defouled \sls (them)\sls*, and spake proudly, 
\p  
\v 35 and swore with wrath, saying, If Judas shall not be taken, and his host, into mine hands, anon when I shall \sls (re)\sls*turn again in peace, I shall burn \sls (down)\sls* this house. And he went out with great wrath. 
\p  
\v 36 And \sls (the)\sls* priests entered, and stood before the face of the altar and \sls (the)\sls* temple, and weeping, they said, 
\p  
\v 37 Thou, Lord, hast chosen this house, for to call to help thy name in it, that it should be an house of prayer and beseeching to \sls (or for)\sls* thy people; 
\p  
\v 38 do thou vengeance in \sls (or to)\sls* this man, and his host, and fall they by \sls (the)\sls* sword; have mind on their blasphemies, and give not to them that they abide \sls (any longer)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 39 And Nicanor went out from Jeru-salem, and applied tents to Bethhoron \sls (or and pitched his tents in Bethhoron)\sls*; and the host of Syria came to him. 
\p  
\v 40 And Judas applied in \sls (or pitched at)\sls* Adasa, with three thousand men. And Judas prayed, and said, 
\p  
\v 41 Lord, an angel went out, and smote an hundred thousand fourscore and five thousands of them, that were sent from king Sennacherib, for they blasphemed thee; 
\p  
\v 42 so all-break this host in our sight today, and \sls (so that)\sls* other men know, that he spake evil on thine holy things \sls (or against thy Temple)\sls*; and deem thou him by \add [or after]\add* the malice of him. 
\p  
\v 43 And the hosts joined battle in the thirteenth day of the month Adar, \em that is, February-March\em*; and the tents, \sls (or the host)\sls*, of Nicanor were all-broken, and he fell down first in \sls (the)\sls* battle. 
\p  
\v 44 Soothly as his host saw, that Nicanor fell down, they casted away their arms, \sls (or weapons)\sls*, and fled. 
\p  
\v 45 And they pursued them the way of one day, from Adasa till men come into Gazara; and they sung in \sls (or with)\sls* trumps after them with signifyings. 
\p  
\v 46 And they went out of all \sls (the)\sls* castles, \sls (or towns)\sls* of Judea in compass, and winnowed them with horns, and again they were converted \sls (or turned back)\sls* to them; and all falled \add [or fell]\add* by \sls (the)\sls* sword, and there was left of them not one. 
\p  
\v 47 And they took the spoils of them \add [in]\add* to prey; and they girded \add [or cutted]\add* off the head of Nicanor, and his right hand which he stretched forth \sls (so)\sls* proudly, and they brought, and hang-ed \sls (them up)\sls* against Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 48 And the people was glad greatly, and they did that day in great gladness; 
\p  
\v 49 and ordained this day for to be done in all years, in the thirteenth day of the month Adar. 
\p  
\v 50 And the land of Judea was still \sls (for)\sls* a few days. 
\c 8  
\cl CHAPTER 8 
\p  
\v 1 And Judas \sls (had)\sls* heard the name \sls (or the fame)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* Romans, that they be mighty in strengths, and accord to all things that be asked of them; and whoever went to them, they ordained with them friendships; 
\p  
\v 2 and that they be mighty in strengths. And they heard \sls (of the)\sls* battles of them, and good virtues, that they did in Galatia, for they wielded them, and led \em them\em* under tribute; 
\p  
\v 3 and how many things they did in the country of Spain, and that they brought into power metals of silver and gold that be there; 
\p  
\v 4 and \sls (that)\sls* they wielded each place with their counsel, and \sls (with)\sls* patience, \em or wisdom\em*, places that were full far from them; and they all-brake kings that came on them from the utmost places of \sls (the)\sls* earth, and they smited them with \sls (a)\sls* great wound; forsooth others give to them tribute by all years. 
\p  
\v 5 And they all-brake in battle Philip, and Perseus, kings \add [or king]\add* of Kittim, and others that bare arms \sls (or weapons)\sls* against them, and wielded them. 
\p  
\v 6 And \em they wielded\em* Antiochus, the great king of Asia, that gave battle to them, and had an hundred and twenty elephants, and multitude of horsemen, and chariots, and full great host all-broken of \sls (or by)\sls* them; 
\p  
\v 7 and that they took him quick \sls (or captured him alive)\sls*, and ordained to him, that he should give great tribute, and they that reigned after him; and that he should give pledges and ordinance, 
\p  
\v 8 in the country of India; and \em they putted out\em* men of Media, and of Lydia, from the best countries of them, and they gave those \em countries\em* taken of \sls (or from)\sls* them to king Eumenes; 
\p  
\v 9 and that they that were with \sls (the)\sls* Greeks, would go, and take away them; 
\p  
\v 10 and the word was known to these \em Romans\em*, and they sent to them one duke, and they fought against them; and many of them fell, and they led their wives captives, and sons, and robbed them; and wielded the land of them, and destroyed the walls of them, and brought them into servage \sls (or into servitude)\sls*, till into this day. 
\p  
\v 11 And they destroyed other realms and isles, that sometime against-stood them, and brought \add [them]\add* into \sls (or under their)\sls* power. 
\p  
\v 12 Forsooth with their friends, and \sls (they)\sls* that had rest in them, they kept friendship, and they wielded realms that were next \sls (or were near)\sls*, and that were far; for whoever heard the name of them, dreaded them. 
\p  
\v 13 For they reigned, to whom they would be in help for to reign; forsooth which they would, they disturbed \sls (or displaced)\sls* from \sls (their)\sls* realm; and they were greatly enhanced \sls (or exalted)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 14 \sls (Yet)\sls* In all these \em Romans\em*, no man bare \sls (a)\sls* diadem, neither was clothed in purple, for to be magnified therein. 
\p  
\v 15 And \add [for]\add* they made to \sls (or for)\sls* them\sls (selves)\sls* a court, and each day they counselled three hundred and twenty, doing counsel evermore of \sls (the)\sls* multitude, \sls (so)\sls* that they do what things be worthy. 
\p  
\v 16 And they betake to one man their mastery, \em either chief governance\em*, by each year, for to be lord of all their land; and all obeish \sls (or obey)\sls* to one, and envy is not, neither wrath among them. 
\p  
\v 17 And Judas chose Eupolemus, the son of John, son of Accos, and Jason, the son of Eleazar, and sent them to Rome, for to ordain with them friend-ship and fellowship; 
\p  
\v 18 and \sls (so)\sls* that they should take away from them the yoke of \sls (the)\sls* Greeks, for they saw that they oppressed the realm of Israel into servage \sls (or into servitude)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 19 And they went to Rome, a full great way, and they entered into the court, and said, 
\p  
\v 20 Judas Maccabeus, and his brethren, and the people of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, sent us to you, for to ordain with you fellow-ship and peace, and for to write together us \sls (as)\sls* your fellows and friends. 
\p  
\v 21 And the word pleased in the sight of them. 
\p  
\v 22 And this is the again-writing, which they again-writed in brazen tables \sls (or wrote upon brass or bronze tablets)\sls*, and sent into Jerusalem, \sls (so)\sls* that it were there a memorial, \em either a thing of mind\em*, of peace and fellowship. 
\p  
\v 23 Be it well to \sls (the)\sls* Romans, and to the folk of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, in the sea and \sls (the)\sls* land, without end; and sword and enemy be far from them. 
\p  
\v 24 That if battle befall to \sls (the)\sls* Romans before, \add [or former]\add*, \sls (or first)\sls*, either to all fellows of them in all the lordship of them, 
\p  
\v 25 the folk of \sls (the)\sls* Jews shall bear help, as time asketh, with \sls (their)\sls* full heart; 
\p  
\v 26 and the \em Romans\em* shall not give, neither privily minister to the \em Jews\em* fighting, wheat, armours, \sls (or arms, or weapons)\sls*, money, ships, as it pleased to \sls (the)\sls* Romans; and they shall keep the commandments of them, and take nothing of \sls (or from)\sls* them. 
\p  
\v 27 Forsooth in like manner, and if battle falleth before \sls (or first)\sls* to the folk of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, \sls (the)\sls* Romans shall help of \sls (or with)\sls*\sls (a)\sls*\add [good]\add* heart, as time suffereth \sls (or alloweth)\sls* them; 
\p  
\v 28 and to \sls (the)\sls*\em Romans\em* helping, wheat shall not be given, neither armours, \sls (nor arms, or weapons)\sls*, money, neither ships, as it pleased to \sls (the)\sls* Romans; and they shall keep the command-ments of them without guile. 
\p  
\v 29 By \add [or After]\add* these words the Romans ordained to the people of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, 
\p  
\v 30 That if after these words, these either they will put anything to, either do away, they shall do of \sls (or by)\sls* their common assent; and whatever things they shall put to, either do away, they shall be steadfast. 
\p  
\v 31 But also of \sls (the)\sls* evils which king Demetrius hath done against them, we have written to him, and we said Why hast thou grieved thy yoke on our friends and fellows, the Jews? 
\p  
\v 32 Therefore if again they shall come to us against thee, we shall do doom to them, and shall fight with thee by land and \sls (by)\sls* sea. 
\c 9  
\cl CHAPTER 9 
\p  
\v 1 In the meantime, where \sls (or when)\sls* Demetrius heard that Nicanor fell, and his host, in battle, he putted to again for to send Bacchides and Alcimus into Judea, and the right half of the battle array with them. 
\p  
\v 2 And they went the way that leadeth into Gilgal, and they setted \sls (up their)\sls* tents in Mesaloth, that is in Arbela; and they occupied it, and slew many persons of men. 
\p  
\v 3 In the first month of the hundred and two and fifty year, they applied the host to Jerusalem \sls (or they pitched their tents near Jerusalem)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 4 And twenty thousand of men, and two thousand of horsemen, have risen, and went into Berea. 
\p  
\v 5 And Judas setted \sls (up his)\sls* tents in Eleasa, and three thousand men chosen \add [or chosen men]\add* with him. 
\p  
\v 6 And they saw the multitude of the host, that they be many, and they dreaded greatly; and many withdrew them\sls (selves)\sls* from \sls (the)\sls* tents \sls (or out of the host)\sls*, and there \sls (were)\sls* left not of them no but eight hundred men. 
\p  
\v 7 And Judas saw that his host fled away, and \sls (that the)\sls* battle constrained him, and he was broken \sls (al)\sls*together in heart, for he had not time to gather them, and he was discomforted. 
\p  
\v 8 And he said to these that were residue, Rise we, and go we to our adversaries, if we shall be able to fight against them. 
\p  
\v 9 And they turned away \sls (from)\sls* him, and said, We shall not be able to, but deliver we \add [now]\add* our own lives, and \sls (re)\sls*turn again we to our brethren, and then we shall fight against them; forsooth we be few. 
\p  
\v 10 And Judas said, Far be it for to do this thing, that we flee from them; and if our time hath nighed, die we in virtue \sls (or bravely)\sls* for our brethren, and give we not crime to our glory. 
\p  
\v 11 And the host \sls (of Bacchides)\sls* moved from \sls (their)\sls* tents, and they stood against them. And \sls (the)\sls* horsemen were parted into two parts, and slingers and archers went before the host, and the first men of battle \sls (were)\sls* all the mighty \sls (men)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 12 Forsooth Bacchides was in the right horn, or battle array. And the legion of two parts came nigh, and cried with \sls (the)\sls* trumps. 
\p  
\v 13 Forsooth and these that were on \add [or of]\add* the part of Judas, cried also, and the earth was moved \sls (al)\sls*together of \sls (or by)\sls* the voice \sls (or the noise)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* hosts, and \sls (the)\sls* battle was joined from the morrowtide till to eventide. 
\p  
\v 14 And Judas saw, that the part of Bacchides’ host was firmer in \sls (or on)\sls* the right half, and all \sls (the)\sls* steadfast in heart came together with him. 
\p  
\v 15 And the right part was all-broken of \sls (or by)\sls* them; and he pursued them unto the hill of Azotus. 
\p  
\v 16 And they that were in the left horn, \em or battle array\em*, saw, that the right horn, \em or battle array\em*, was all-broken, and they pursued \sls (or followed)\sls* at the back after Judas, and them that were with him. 
\p  
\v 17 And the battle was made grievous, and there fell many wounded of these and of them. 
\p  
\v 18 And Judas fell, and the others fled. 
\p  
\v 19 And Jonathan and Simon took their brother Judas, and buried him in the sepulchre of his fathers, in the city of Modin. 
\p  
\v 20 And all Israel bewept him with great wailing, and mourned \sls (for)\sls* many days, and said, 
\p  
\v 21 How fell the mighty \sls (man)\sls*, that made Israel safe \sls (or who saved Israel)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 22 And other words of \sls (the)\sls* battles of Judas, and of \sls (the)\sls* virtues that he did, and of his greatnesses, be not written \sls (here)\sls*; for those \add [or they]\add* were full many. 
\p  
\v 23 And it was done, after the death of Judas, all wicked men in all the coasts of Israel rose out \sls (or rose up)\sls*, and all that wrought wickedness came forth. 
\p  
\v 24 In those days full great hunger was made, and all the country of them betook themselves to Bacchides with them. 
\p  
\v 25 And Bacchides chose unpious men, and ordained them lords of the country. 
\p  
\v 26 And they asked out \sls (or about)\sls*, and sought the friends of Judas, and brought them to Bacchides; and he avenged on them, and scorned \sls (them)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 27 And great tribulation was made in Israel, what manner was not from the day in which a prophet was not seen in Israel. 
\p  
\v 28 And all the friends of Judas were gathered, and said to Jonathan, 
\p  
\v 29 Since thy brother Judas is dead, there is no man like him, that shall go out against \sls (our)\sls* enemies, Bacchides and them that be \sls (the)\sls* enemies of our folk. 
\p  
\v 30 Therefore now we choose thee today for to be prince and duke to us for him, for to fight our battle\sls (s)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 31 And \sls (so)\sls* Jonathan received in that time the princehood, and rose \sls (up)\sls* in the place of Judas, his brother. 
\p  
\v 32 And Bacchides knew \sls (this)\sls*, and sought for to slay him. 
\p  
\v 33 And Jonathan knew \sls (this)\sls*, and Simon, his brother, and all that were with him, and \add [they]\add* fled into \sls (the)\sls* desert of Tekoa, and sat together at the water of the lake Asphar. 
\p  
\v 34 And Bacchides knew \sls (this)\sls*, and in the day of sabbath he came, and all his host, over \sls (the)\sls* Jordan. 
\p  
\v 35 And \em Jonathan\em* sent his brother \sls (John)\sls*, \sls (a)\sls* leader of \em that\em* people, and prayed \sls (the)\sls* Nabathites or Nabateans, his friends, that he should betake to them his apparel, that was plenteous. 
\p  
\v 36 And \sls (the)\sls* sons of Jambri went out of Medaba, and caught John, and all \sls (the)\sls* things that he had, and went away, having \sls (or taking)\sls* those things. 
\p  
\v 37 After these words it was told again to Jonathan, and Simon, his brother, that the sons of Jambri make great wed-dings, and wed a wife of Nadabath, the daughter of one of the great princes of Canaan, with great pride and apparel. 
\p  
\v 38 And they bethought on the blood of John, their brother, and went up, and hid themselves under \sls (the)\sls* cover-ing of the hill. 
\p  
\v 39 And they raised \sls (up)\sls* their eyes, and saw, and lo! noise, and great apparel; and a spouse, \em or \+sls (the)\+sls* husband\em*, came forth, and his friends, and his brethren, against \sls (or towards)\sls* them, with tympans, and musics, and many arms. 
\p  
\v 40 And they rose \sls (up)\sls* to \sls (or against)\sls* them from \sls (the)\sls* ambushments, and slew them, and many wounded fell down, and the residues fled into the hill, and they took all the spoils of them; 
\p  
\v 41 and \sls (the)\sls* weddings were converted into mourning, and voice \sls (or the sound)\sls* of their musics into wailing. 
\p  
\v 42 And they avenged the vengeance of their brother’s blood, and \add [they]\add*\sls (re)\sls*-turned again to the brink of \sls (the)\sls* Jordan. 
\p  
\v 43 And Bacchides heard, and came in the day of sabbaths till to the utmost part of \sls (the)\sls* Jordan, in great strength. 
\p  
\v 44 And Jonathan said to his \sls (men)\sls*, Rise we \sls (up)\sls*, and fight against our enemies; for it is not today as yesterday, and the third day ago. 
\p  
\v 45 For lo! \sls (the)\sls* battle \em is\em* even against \sls (or before us)\sls*; soothly the water of \sls (the)\sls* Jordan \em is\em* on this half and on that half, and rivers, and marshes, and forests \add [or wild woods]\add*, and there is no place of turning away \sls (or aside)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 46 Now therefore cry ye into heaven, \sls (so)\sls* that ye be delivered from \sls (the)\sls* hand of your enemies. 
\p  
\v 47 And \sls (the)\sls* battle was joined. And Jonathan straightened out \sls (or stretched forth)\sls* his hand, for to smite Bacchides, and he turned away from him behind. 
\p  
\v 48 And Jonathan skipped down, and they that were with him, into \sls (the)\sls* Jordan, and swam over \sls (the)\sls* Jordan to them. 
\p  
\v 49 And there fell of Bacchides part in that day a thousand men, 
\p  
\v 50 and they, \em that is, Bacchides and his men\em*, \sls (re)\sls*turned again into Jerusalem; and \sls (re)\sls*builded \sls (the)\sls* strong cities in Judea, the strength \sls (or the stronghold)\sls* that was in Jericho, and in Emmaus, and in Bethhoron, and Bethel, and Thamnatha, Pharathoni, and Taphon, with high walls, and gates, and locks. 
\p  
\v 51 And he setted keeping in them, \sls (so)\sls* that they should haunt enmities in \sls (or upon)\sls* Israel; 
\p  
\v 52 and he strengthened the city \sls (of)\sls* Bethsura, and Gazara, and the high tower, and putted in them helps, and apparel of meats \sls (or food)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 53 And he took the sons of princes of the country in \sls (or for)\sls* hostage\sls (s)\sls*, \em or pledges\em*, and putted them in the high tower in Jerusalem, in keeping. 
\p  
\v 54 And in the hundred year and three and fifty \add [or fiftieth]\add*, in the second month, Alcimus commanded \sls (that)\sls* the walls of the holy inner house for to be destroyed, and the works of \sls (the)\sls* prophets for to be destroyed, 
\p  
\v 55 and he began for to destroy \sls (them)\sls*. In that time Alcimus was smitten, and the works of him were hindered. And his mouth was closed, and he was dissolved, \em either made feeble\em*, by palsy, neither he might speak more a word, and command of \sls (or to)\sls* his house. 
\p  
\v 56 And Alcimus was dead in that time, with great torment. 
\p  
\v 57 And Bacchides saw, that Alcimus was dead, and he \sls (re)\sls*turned again to the king, and the land was still two years. 
\p  
\v 58 And all \sls (the)\sls* wicked men thought, saying, Lo! Jonathan, and they that be with him, dwell in silence, and trust; now therefore bring we Bacchides, and he shall take them all in one night. 
\p  
\v 59 And they went forth, and gave counsel to him. 
\p  
\v 60 And he rose \sls (up)\sls*, for to come with much host. And he sent epistles privily to his fellows, that were in Judea, that they should catch Jonathan, and them that were with him; but they might not, for their counsel was known to them. 
\p  
\v 61 And \em Jonathan\em* caught \sls (those)\sls* of men of the country, that were princes of knighthood, fifty men, and slew them. 
\p  
\v 62 And Jonathan and Simon went, and they that were with him, into Bethbasi, that is in \sls (the)\sls* desert, and \sls (re)\sls*builded the destroyed things there-of, and made it strong. 
\p  
\v 63 And Bacchides knew \sls (this)\sls*, and gathered all his multitude, and announced to them that were of Judea. 
\p  
\v 64 And he came, and setted \sls (up)\sls* tents above Bethbasi, and fought against it many days, and made engines \sls (of war)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 65 And Jonathan left Simon, his brother, in the city, and went out into the coun-try, and came with \sls (a)\sls* number \sls (of men)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 66 and smote Odomera, and his brethren, and \sls (the)\sls* sons of Phasiron, in the tabernacles of them \sls (or tents)\sls*, 
\p  
\v 67 and \add [he]\add* began for to smite, and wax in virtues \sls (or increase his forces)\sls*. Simon soothly, and they that were with him, went out of the city, and burnt \sls (up the)\sls* engines \sls (of war)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 68 And they fought against Bacchides, and he was all-broken of \sls (or by)\sls* them; and they tormented him greatly, for his counsel and his assailing was void. 
\p  
\v 69 And he was wroth against wicked men, that gave counsel to him for to come into their country, and slew many of them; forsooth he thought with others for to go into his country. 
\p  
\v 70 And Jonathan knew, and sent legates to him, for to make peace with him, and to yield to him \sls (the)\sls* prisoners. 
\p  
\v 71 And willfully he took \sls (or accepted)\sls*, and did by \add [or after]\add* his words, and swore that he should not do to him any evil in all the days of his life. 
\p  
\v 72 And he yielded to him the captivity, \em that is, \+sls (the Jewish)\+sls* prisoners\em*, which he took by prey before \sls (out)\sls* of the land of Judea. And he \sls (re)\sls*turned, and went into his land, and putted no more for to come into his coasts. 
\p  
\v 73 And \sls (the)\sls* sword ceased from Israel. And Jonathan dwelled in Michmash, and there Jonathan began for to deem the people, and he destroyed the un-faithful \add [or unpious]\add* men \sls (out)\sls* of Israel. 
\c 10  
\cl CHAPTER 10 
\p  
\v 1 And in the hundred and sixtieth year Alexander, the son of Antiochus, went up, that is named noble \sls (or who was surnamed Epiphanes)\sls*, \add [or that is named noble, went up]\add*, and occupied Ptolemais; and they received him, and he reigned there. 
\p  
\v 2 And king Demetrius heard, and gathered an host full copious, and went out against him into battle. 
\p  
\v 3 And Demetrius sent \add [an]\add* epistle to Jonathan with peaceable words, for to magnify him. 
\p  
\v 4 For he said, Before take we for to make peace with him, before that he make \sls (an accord)\sls* with Alexander against us; 
\p  
\v 5 for he shall have mind of or on all \sls (the)\sls* evils, that we have done against him, and against his brother\sls (s)\sls*, and against his folk. 
\p  
\v 6 And he gave to him power to gather \sls (an)\sls* host, and for to make arms, and him for to be his fellow. And he commanded \sls (that the)\sls* hostages, \em either \+sls (the)\+sls* pledges\em*, that were in the high tower, for to be given to him. 
\p  
\v 7 And Jonathan came into Jerusalem, and read \sls (the)\sls* epistles \sls (or the letter)\sls*, in \sls (the)\sls* hearing of all the people, and of them that were in the high tower. 
\p  
\v 8 And they dreaded with great dread, for they heard, that the king gave him power to gather an host. 
\p  
\v 9 And \sls (the)\sls* hostages were betaken to Jonathan, and he yielded them \sls (back)\sls* to their fathers and mothers. 
\p  
\v 10 And Jonathan dwelt in Jerusalem, and began for to build and renew the city. 
\p  
\v 11 And he said to men doing \sls (the)\sls* works, that they should make up the walls, and the hill of Zion in compass, with square stones to \sls (or for)\sls* strengthening; and they did so. 
\p  
\v 12 And \sls (the)\sls* aliens fled, that were in the strengths \sls (or in the strongholds)\sls*, which Bacchides had builded; 
\p  
\v 13 and each man left his place, and went into his \sls (own)\sls* land. 
\p  
\v 14 Only in Bethsura dwelt some of them, that forsook the law and the behests of God; for why this was to \sls (or for)\sls* them the \sls (place of)\sls* refuge. 
\p  
\v 15 And Alexander the king heard \sls (the)\sls* promises, that Demetrius \sls (had)\sls* promised to Jonathan, and they told to him \sls (of)\sls* the battles and virtues which he did, and his brethren, and the travails which they travailed. 
\p  
\v 16 And he said, Whether we shall find any such man? And now make we him our friend and fellow. 
\p  
\v 17 And he wrote \sls (an)\sls* epistle, and sent \sls (it to him)\sls*, by these words, saying, 
\p  
\v 18 King Alexander to Jonathan, brother, health. 
\p  
\v 19 We have heard of thee, that thou art a mighty man in strengths, and art able that thou be our friend. 
\p  
\v 20 And now we ordain thee today \sls (to be the)\sls* highest priest of thy folk, and that thou be called \sls (the)\sls* friend of the king. And he sent to him purple, and a golden crown, that thou feel with us what things be ours, and keep friendships to \sls (or with)\sls* us. 
\p  
\v 21 And Jonathan clothed him\sls (self)\sls* with an holy stole, in the seventh month, in the hundred and sixtieth year, in the solemn day of Scenopegia \sls (or Feast of Tabernacles)\sls*. And he gathered an host \sls (or army)\sls*, and made copious or plen-teous arms \sls (or prepared many weapons)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 22 And Demetrius heard these words, and was made full sorrowful, and said, 
\p  
\v 23 What have we done this thing, that Alexander before-occupied us, for to catch \sls (the)\sls* friendship of \sls (or with the)\sls* Jews, to his \sls (own)\sls* strengthening? 
\p  
\v 24 And I shall write to him praying words, and \sls (promise him)\sls* dignities, and gifts, \sls (so)\sls* that he be with me in help. 
\p  
\v 25 And \sls (so)\sls* he wrote to him by these words, King Demetrius to the folk of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, health. 
\p  
\v 26 For ye kept to us covenant, and dwelt in our friendship, and went not to our enemies, we heard, and joyed. 
\p  
\v 27 And now last ye yet for to keep to us faith; and we shall \sls (re)\sls*quite to you good things, for these things that ye did to \sls (or for)\sls* us, 
\p  
\v 28 and we shall forgive to you many \add [givings of]\add* rents, and we shall give gifts to you. 
\p  
\v 29 And now I assoil \sls (or I absolve)\sls* you, and all \sls (the)\sls* Jews, of tributes, and I forgive \em to you\em* the prices of salt, and forgive crowns \sls (or crown taxes)\sls*, 
\p  
\v 30 and the third part of \sls (the)\sls* seed; and I leave to you from this day and afterward, the half part of \sls (the)\sls* fruit of the tree\sls (s)\sls*, that is of my portion, \sls (so)\sls* that it be not taken of the land of Judea, and of \sls (the)\sls* three cities that be added thereto, of Samaria and Galilee, from this day and into all time. 
\p  
\v 31 And \sls (let)\sls* Jerusalem be holy, and free, with his \sls (or its)\sls* coasts; and tithes and tributes be of it. 
\p  
\v 32 Also I forgive the power of the high tower, that is in Jerusalem; and I give it to the high or highest priest, that he ordain therein men, whichever he shall choose, that shall keep it. 
\p  
\v 33 And each person of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, that is captive \sls (out)\sls* of the land of Judea, in all my realm, I deliver free willfully, \em or without money\em*, that all be absolved of their tributes, yea, of their beasts. 
\p  
\v 34 And all solemn days, and sabbaths, and new moons, and all days ordained, and three days before the solemn day, and three days after the solemn day, all these be days of immunity, \em or franchise\em*, and of remission, to all \sls (the)\sls* Jews that be in my realm. 
\p  
\v 35 And no man shall have power for to do anything, and move needs, \em or causes\em*, against any of them in \sls (or for)\sls* any cause. 
\p  
\v 36 And that there be written \sls (in)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* Jews in the king’s host, \sls (up)\sls* to thirty thousands of men; and plenties shall be given to them, as it behoov-eth to all \sls (the)\sls* hosts of the king. 
\p  
\v 37 And of them shall be ordained, that be in the great strengths \sls (or strongholds)\sls* of the king; of them shall be ordained over needs of the realm, that be done of faith, and \sls (their)\sls* princes be of them; and walk they in their laws, as the king commanded in the land of Judea. 
\p  
\v 38 And \sls (the)\sls* three cities, that be added to Judea of \sls (or from)\sls* the country of Samaria, be areckoned, \em or deemed\em*, with Judea; \sls (so)\sls* that they be under one, and obey not to \sls (any)\sls* other power, no but to the highest priest; 
\p  
\v 39 \sls (As for)\sls* Ptolemais, and the coasts thereof, which I have given \sls (as)\sls* a gift to holy men that be in Jerusalem, to needful costs of saints \sls (or the Temple)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 40 And I shall give in each year fifteen thousand of shekels of silver, of the king’s reasons, that pertain to me; 
\p  
\v 41 and all that is residue, which they that were over \sls (the)\sls* needs yielded not in former years, from this time they shall give into the works of the house. 
\p  
\v 42 And over this, five thousand shekels of silver, which they took of reason of holy things by each year; and these things shall pertain to \sls (the)\sls* priests, that use \add [or be set in]\add* ministry. 
\p  
\v 43 And whoever shall flee to the temple that is in Jerusalem, and in all \sls (the)\sls* coasts thereof, and be guilty to the king, in any cause, be dismissed, \em or released\em*; and have they free all things, that be to them in my realm. 
\p  
\v 44 And to build, \em or restore\em*, works of holy things \sls (or the works of the Temple)\sls*, costs, \em or expenses\em*, shall be given \sls (out)\sls* of the king’s reason, \em or rent\em*, \sls (or out of the king’s accounts)\sls*, 
\p  
\v 45 and for to build out the walls of Jerusalem; and for to make \sls (them)\sls* strong in compass, expenses shall be given \sls (out)\sls* of the king’s reason, \em or rent\em*, for to make out \sls (the)\sls* walls in Judea. 
\p  
\v 46 As Jonathan and the people heard these words, they believed not to them, neither received \em them\em*; for they had \sls (in)\sls* mind of the great malice that he had done in Israel, and \sls (that he)\sls* had troubled them greatly. 
\p  
\v 47 And it pleased \sls (al)\sls*together to them in \sls (or with)\sls* Alexander, for he was to them \sls (the)\sls* prince of words of peace, and to him they bare help in all days. 
\p  
\v 48 And king Alexander gathered a great host, and moved \sls (his)\sls* tents against Demetrius. 
\p  
\v 49 And the kings joined battle, and the host of Demetrius fled; and Alex-ander pursued him, and lay on them; 
\p  
\v 50 and the battle was full strong, till the sun went down, and Demetrius fell in that day. 
\p  
\v 51 And Alexander sent to Ptolemy, king of Egypt, legates by \sls (or ambass-adors with)\sls* these words, and said, 
\p  
\v 52 For I came again into my realm, and sat in the seat of my fathers; and I have wielded princehood, and I have all-broken Demetrius, and have wield-ed our country; 
\p  
\v 53 and I have joined fight with him, and he and his hosts be all-fouled \add [or is broken \+sls (al)\+sls*together]\add* of \sls (or by)\sls* us, and we sat in the seat of his realm. 
\p  
\v 54 And now ordain we together friendship, and give thy daughter \sls (as)\sls* a wife to me, and I shall be thy daughter\sls (’s)\sls* husband; and I shall give to thee gifts, and to her dignity. 
\p  
\v 55 And king Ptolemy answered, say-ing, Blessed be the day in which thou \sls (re)\sls*turnedest again to the land of thy fathers, and hast sat in the seat \sls (or on the throne)\sls* of the realm of them. 
\p  
\v 56 And now I shall do to thee which things thou hast written; but come thou against me to \sls (or meet me in)\sls* Ptolemais, \sls (so)\sls* that we see us together, and I promise to thee, as thou saidest. 
\p  
\v 57 And Ptolemy went out of Egypt, he and Cleopatra, his daughter; and he came to Ptolemais, in the hundred and two and sixtieth year. 
\p  
\v 58 And Alexander, the king, came to him; and he gave to him Cleopatra, his daughter, and made his weddings at Ptolemais, as kings in great glory \sls (do)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 59 And king Alexander wrote to Jonathan, that he should come against him \sls (or should come to meet him)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 60 And he went with glory to Ptolemais, and met there \sls (the)\sls* two kings, and gave to them much silver, and gold, and gifts; and found grace in the sight of them. 
\p  
\v 61 And men of Israel, full of venom, came together against him, wicked men, asking against him, and \sls (or but)\sls* the king took no attention to them; 
\p  
\v 62 and commanded Jonathan for to be made naked of his clothes, and him for to be clothed in purple; and they did so. 
\p  
\v 63 And the king setted him for to sit with him, and said to his princes, Go ye out with him into the middle of the city, and preach ye, that no man ask against him of \sls (or about)\sls* any need, \em or cause\em*, neither any man be heavy to him of \sls (or for)\sls* any reason. 
\p  
\v 64 And it was done, as they that \sls (had)\sls* asked, \add [or appealed \+sls (against)\+sls* him]\add*, \sls (or when they that had accused him)\sls*, saw his glory that was preached, and him covered with purple, all fled \sls (away)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 65 And the king magnified him, and wrote him among the first friends, and putted him \sls (a)\sls* duke, and partner, \em or fellow\em*, of \sls (his)\sls* princehood. 
\p  
\v 66 And Jonathan \sls (re)\sls*turned again into Jerusalem, with peace and gladness. 
\p  
\v 67 In the hundred year and five and sixtieth, Demetrius, the son of Demetrius, came from Crete into the land of his fathers. 
\p  
\v 68 And king Alexander heard, and was made full sorrowful, and \sls (re)\sls*turned again to Antioch. 
\p  
\v 69 And Demetrius ordained Apollonius duke, that was sovereign of Celosyria \sls (or who was the governor of Greater Syria)\sls*; and he gathered his great host, and came to Jamnia; and sent to Jonathan, the highest priest, and said, 
\p  
\v 70 Thou alone against-standest us; I am made into scorn and shame \sls (or reproof)\sls* therefore, for thou hauntest power in \sls (the)\sls* hills against us. 
\p  
\v 71 Now therefore if thou trustest in thy virtues \sls (or thy strength)\sls*, come down to us into the field; and there assemble \add [or comparison]\add* we together, for with me is \sls (the)\sls* virtue \sls (or power)\sls* of battles. 
\p  
\v 72 Ask thou, and learn who I am, and others that be in help to me, and which say, that your foot may not stand against our face, for thy fathers were converted into flight twice into \sls (or in)\sls* their \sls (own)\sls* land. 
\p  
\v 73 And now how shalt thou be able to sustain \sls (the)\sls* multitude of horsemen, and so great host in the field, where is no stone, nor rock, neither place of fleeing? 
\p  
\v 74 Soothly as Jonathan heard these words of Apollonius, he was moved in \sls (his)\sls* heart; and he chose ten thousand men, and went out from Jerusalem, and Simon, his brother, came to him into help. 
\p  
\v 75 And they applied \sls (or pitched their)\sls* tents in Joppa, and it, \em that is, the people of Joppa\em*, shutted out him \add [or shut him out]\add* from the city, for Joppa was the keeping of Apollonius; 
\p  
\v 76 and he fought against it, \em that is, Jonathan fought against Joppa\em*. And they were aghast, that were within the city, and opened to him; and \sls (so)\sls* Jonathan wielded Joppa. 
\p  
\v 77 And Apollonius heard, and moved three thousand of horsemen, and much host; and went to Azotus, as making \sls (the)\sls* way. And anon he went out into the field, for that he had \sls (a)\sls* multitude of horsemen, and he trusted in them; 
\p  
\v 78 and Jonathan pursued him into Azotus, and they joined battle. 
\p  
\v 79 And Apollonius left in \sls (the)\sls* tents a thousand horsemen behind them privily. 
\p  
\v 80 And Jonathan knew that ambush-ments were behind him, and they environed his tents \sls (or his host)\sls*, and casted darts into the people, from the morrow till to eventide. 
\p  
\v 81 Forsooth the people stood, as Jonathan commanded, and the horses of them travailed out. 
\p  
\v 82 And Simon led out his host, and joined \sls (battle)\sls* against the legion; for-sooth \sls (the)\sls* horsemen were made weary, and were all-broken of him, and fled. 
\p  
\v 83 And they that were scattered in the field, fled into Azotus; and entered into the house of Dagon \add [or into Bethdagon]\add*, their idol, \sls (so)\sls* that there they should deliver themselves. 
\p  
\v 84 And Jonathan burnt Azotus, and \sls (the)\sls* cities that were in compass thereof, and took \sls (the)\sls* spoils of them; and he burnt in \sls (or with)\sls* fire the temple of Dagon, and them that \sls (had)\sls* fled into it. 
\p  
\v 85 And there were that fell by \sls (the)\sls* sword with them that were burnt, almost eight thousand men. 
\p  
\v 86 And from thence Jonathan moved \sls (his)\sls* tents, and applied them to \sls (or encamped at)\sls* Ascalon; and they went out of the city against him in great glory. 
\p  
\v 87 And Jonathan \sls (re)\sls*turned again to Jerusalem with his men, having many spoils. 
\p  
\v 88 And it was done, as king Alexander heard these words, he putted to yet for to glorify Jonathan. 
\p  
\v 89 And he sent to him a golden lace, \em either \+sls (an)\+sls* ouch\em*, \sls (\+em or clasp\+em*)\sls*, as custom is to be given to \sls (the)\sls* cousins of kings; and he gave to him Ekron, and all \sls (the)\sls* coasts thereof in possession. 
\c 11  
\cl CHAPTER 11 
\p  
\v 1 And the king of Egypt gathered an host, as gravel that is about the brink of the sea, and many ships; and sought for to wield the realm of Alexander in guile, and add it to his realm. 
\p  
\v 2 And he went out into Syria with peaceable words, and they opened to him cities, and came to him; for why king Alexander commanded \sls (them)\sls* for to go out against \sls (or to meet)\sls* him, for he was \sls (the)\sls* father of the king’s wife. 
\p  
\v 3 Soothly when Ptolemy entered into a city, he putted keepings of knights in each city. 
\p  
\v 4 And as he nighed to Azotus, they showed to him the temple of Dagon burnt in fire, and Azotus, and other things thereof \sls (that)\sls* were destroyed, and \sls (the)\sls* bodies cast forth, and the burials of them that were slain in battle, which they made beside the way. 
\p  
\v 5 And they told to the king that Jonathan did these things, for to make envy to him; and the king was still. 
\p  
\v 6 And Jonathan came to the king with glory into Joppa, and they greeted them together; and they slept there. 
\p  
\v 7 And Jonathan went with the king till to the flood that is called Eleutherus, and \sls (re)\sls*turned again into Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 8 Soothly king Ptolemy wielded the lordship of \sls (the)\sls* cities till to Seleucia, by the sea coast, and thought against Alexander evil counsels; 
\p  
\v 9 and sent legates \sls (or ambassadors)\sls* to Demetrius, and said, Come thou, make we betwixt us \sls (a)\sls* covenant, and I shall give to thee my daughter, whom Alexander hath, and thou shalt reign in the realm of thy father. 
\p  
\v 10 For it rueth me, that I gave to him my daughter; for he sought for to slay me. 
\p  
\v 11 And he despised him therefore, for he coveted the realm of him. 
\p  
\v 12 And he took away his daughter, and gave her to Demetrius, and aliened \sls (or alienated)\sls* him\sls (self)\sls* from Alexander; and his enmities were made known. 
\p  
\v 13 And Ptolemy entered into Antioch, and putted two diadems \sls (on)\sls*to his head, of Egypt and of Asia. 
\p  
\v 14 Forsooth Alexander, the king, was in Cilicia in those days, for they rebelled, that were in those places. 
\p  
\v 15 And Alexander heard, and came to him into battle; and Ptolemy, the king, brought forth the host, and came to him in \sls (or with a)\sls* strong hand, and drove him away. 
\p  
\v 16 And Alexander flew into Arabia, for to be defended there; soothly king Ptolemy was enhanced \sls (or was exalted)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 17 And Zabdiel of Arabia took away Alexander’s head, and sent \sls (it)\sls* to Ptolemy. 
\p  
\v 18 And king Ptolemy was dead in the third day \sls (after)\sls*; and they that were in \sls (the)\sls* strengths perished, of them that were within the castles \sls (or villages)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 19 And Demetrius reigned in the hundred year and seven and sixtieth. 
\p  
\v 20 In those days Jonathan gathered them that were in Judea, for to overcome the high tower, that is in Jerusalem; and they made against it many engines. 
\p  
\v 21 And some wicked men, that hated their \sls (own)\sls* folk, went to the king Demetrius \add [or went to king Demetrius]\add*, and told to him, that Jonathan besieged the high tower. 
\p  
\v 22 And as he heard \sls (this)\sls*, he was wroth, and anon he came to Ptolemais, and wrote to Jonathan, that he should not besiege the high tower, but should come to him in haste, to speak together. 
\p  
\v 23 Soothly as Jonathan heard \sls (this)\sls*, he commanded for to besiege \sls (it still)\sls*; and he chose \sls (some)\sls* of the elder men of Israel, and \sls (the)\sls* priests, and gave him\sls (self)\sls* to peril. 
\p  
\v 24 And he took gold, and silver, and cloth\sls (es)\sls*, and many other presents; and went to the king, to Ptolemais, and found grace in the sight of him. 
\p  
\v 25 And some wicked men of his folk \sls (had)\sls* asked \sls (or had spoken)\sls* against him; 
\p  
\v 26 and \sls (yet)\sls* the king did to him, as they that were before him, did to him; and he enhanced \sls (or exalted)\sls* him in \sls (the)\sls* sight of all his friends, 
\p  
\v 27 and ordained to him princehood of priesthood, and whatever other precious things \sls (that)\sls* he had before; and made him prince of his friends. 
\p  
\v 28 And Jonathan asked of the king, that he should make Judea free, and \sls (also the)\sls* three princehoods of three places, and Samaria, and nigh coasts thereof; and he promised to him \sls (in return)\sls* three hundred talents. 
\p  
\v 29 And the king consented, and wrote to Jonathan epistles of \sls (or about)\sls* all these things, containing \sls (or in)\sls* this manner. 
\p  
\v 30 King Demetrius to Jonathan, brother, health, and to the folk of \sls (the)\sls* Jews. 
\p  
\v 31 The ensample \sls (or copy)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* epistle, which we have written to Lasthenes, our father, of \sls (or about)\sls* you, we sent to you, that ye should know. 
\p  
\v 32 King Demetrius to Lasthenes, father \sls (or our kinsman)\sls*, health. 
\p  
\v 33 To the people of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, our friends, and keeping which things be just with us, we deemed for to do well, for \sls (the)\sls* benignity of them that they have with us. 
\p  
\v 34 Therefore we ordained to them, all the coasts of Judea, and \sls (the)\sls* three cities of offerings, Lydda, and Ramath-aim, and Apherema, that be added to Judea, and \sls (or from)\sls* Samaria, and all the nigh coast of them, for to be sequestered, \em or parted\em*, to all men doing sacrifice in Jerusalem, for these things that the king took before of \sls (or received from)\sls* them by all years, and for \sls (the)\sls* fruits of the earth, and of apples. 
\p  
\v 35 And of other things that pertained to us, of tithes, and tributes, from this time \sls (forth)\sls* we forgive to them; and the plain places of salt-making, and the crowns that were borne to us \sls (or the crown taxes, that be due to us)\sls*, all things we grant to them; 
\p  
\v 36 and nothing of these shall be void, from this \em time\em* and into all time. 
\p  
\v 37 Now therefore busy ye for to make \sls (an)\sls* ensample \sls (or a copy)\sls* of these things, and be it given to Jonathan, and be \sls (it)\sls* put in the holy mount, and in the solemn \add [or the holy]\add* place. 
\p  
\v 38 And king Demetrius saw, that the land was still in his sight, and that nothing against-stood him, and left \sls (or let go)\sls* all his host, each man into his \sls (own)\sls* place, except the strange host \sls (or except for the host of strangers, or of foreigners)\sls*, that he drew from \sls (the)\sls* isles of \sls (the)\sls* heathen men; and all the hosts of his fathers \em were\em* enemies to him. 
\p  
\v 39 Forsooth one Tryphon was of the parts of Alexander before, and he saw that all the host grumbled against Demetrius; and he went to Imalcue \sls (the)\sls* Arabian, that nourished \sls (up)\sls*, \sls (or nursed)\sls* Antiochus, the son of Alexander. 
\p  
\v 40 And he made great instance \sls (or great insistence)\sls* to him, that he should betake him to him, for to reign instead of his father; and \add [he]\add* told out to him, how great things Demetrius had done, and the enmities of his hosts against him; and he dwelt there many days. 
\p  
\v 41 And Jonathan sent to king Demetrius, that he should cast out them, that were in the high tower in Jerusalem, and which were in \sls (the)\sls* helps, \em or strengths\em*, \sls (\+em or strongholds\+em*)\sls*, for they impugned Israel. 
\p  
\v 42 And Demetrius sent to Jonathan, and said, Not only this I shall do to \sls (or for)\sls* thee, and thy folk, but I shall make thee noble by glory, and thy folk, when it shall be covenable \sls (or opportune)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 43 Now therefore rightly thou shalt do, if thou shalt send men in to help to me, for all mine host went away. 
\p  
\v 44 And Jonathan sent to him three thousand of strong men, to Antioch; and they came to the king, and the king delighted in the coming of them. 
\p  
\v 45 And there came together that were of the city sixscore thousand of men, and would slay the king. 
\p  
\v 46 And the king fled into the hall. And they that were of the city occupied the ways of the city, and begun for to fight. 
\p  
\v 47 And the king called \sls (the)\sls* Jews into help, and all came together to him, and all were scattered by the city; and slew in that day an hundred thousand of men, 
\p  
\v 48 and \add [they]\add* burnt the city, and took many spoils in that day, and delivered the king. 
\p  
\v 49 And they saw, \sls (they)\sls* that were of the city, that \sls (the)\sls* Jews had taken the city as they would; and they were made unsteadfast in their soul, and cried to the king with prayers, and said, 
\p  
\v 50 Give to us right hands, and cease the Jews for to fight against us and the city. 
\p  
\v 51 And they casted away their arms, \sls (or weapons)\sls*, and made peace. And \sls (the)\sls* Jews were glorified in the sight of the king, and in the sight of all men that were in his realm, and were named in the realm. And they went again into Jerusalem, having many spoils. 
\p  
\v 52 And king Demetrius sat in the seat \sls (or throne)\sls* of his realm, and the land was still \sls (or quiet)\sls* in his sight. 
\p  
\v 53 And he lied \sls (in)\sls* all things, what-ever he said, and alienated him from Jonathan, and yielded not to him by benefices, which he had given to him; and \em Demetrius\em* travailed him greatly. 
\p  
\v 54 After these things Tryphon \sls (re)\sls*turn-ed again, and \sls (had)\sls* Antiochus, a young child, with him; and \sls (he)\sls* reigned, and putted on him a diadem. 
\p  
\v 55 And all \sls (the)\sls* hosts were gathered \sls (un)\sls*to him, which king Demetrius \sls (had)\sls* scattered; and they fought against him, and he flew, and turned backs. 
\p  
\v 56 And Tryphon took \sls (the)\sls* beasts, \em that is, \+sls (the)\+sls* elephants of the host of Demetrius\em*, and wielded Antioch. 
\p  
\v 57 And Antiochus the young wrote to Jonathan, and said, I ordain to thee \sls (the high)\sls* priesthood, and I ordain thee on \sls (the)\sls* four cities, \sls (and)\sls* that thou be \sls (one)\sls* of the king’s friends. 
\p  
\v 58 And he sent to him golden vessels, into ministry \sls (or for service)\sls*, and gave to him power to drink in gold, and for to be in purple, and for to have a golden lace, \em either \+sls (an)\+sls* ouch\em*, \sls (\+em or buckle\+em*)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 59 And he ordained Simon, his brother, duke from the ends of Tyre, till to the ends of Egypt. 
\p  
\v 60 And Jonathan went out, and walked over the flood \sls (or beyond the river)\sls* by the cities; and all the host of Syria was gathered to him into help. And he came to Ascalon, and they of the city came against him worshipfully \sls (or with due honour or deference)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 61 And from thence he went to Gaza, and they that were at Gaza closed \sls (up)\sls* them\sls (selves)\sls*\sls (al)\sls*together, and he besieged it. And he burnt what things were in compass of the city, and spoiled it by \sls (or for)\sls* prey. 
\p  
\v 62 And \sls (the)\sls* men of Gaza prayed Jonathan, and he gave to them \sls (the)\sls* right hand, \em either peace\em*. And he took the sons of them in\sls (to)\sls* hostage \sls (or for hostages)\sls*, or \sls (as)\sls* pledges, and he sent them into Jerusalem, and walked through the country till to Damascus. 
\p  
\v 63 And Jonathan heard, that the princes of Demetrius trespassed in Kedesh, that is in Galilee, with much host, willing \sls (or desiring)\sls* to remove him from \sls (the)\sls* need of the realm; 
\p  
\v 64 and he came against them \sls (or he came to meet them)\sls*. Forsooth he left Simon, his brother, within the province. 
\p  
\v 65 And Simon applied to \sls (or encamp-ed at)\sls* Bethsura, and fought against it \sls (for)\sls* many days, and closed \sls (up)\sls*\sls (al)\sls*to-gether them. 
\p  
\v 66 And they asked of him for to take right hands, and he gave \sls (it)\sls* to them. And he casted out them from thence, and took the city, and putted therein \sls (a)\sls* strength \sls (or a stronghold)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 67 And Jonathan and his host applied to the water of Gennesar, \sls (or encamped at the Lake of Gennesaret, or by the Sea of Galilee)\sls*, and before the light they walked in the light \add [or the field]\add* of Asor. 
\p  
\v 68 And lo! the hosts of aliens came against \sls (or met)\sls* them in the field, and setted to him espies, \sls (or men in ambush)\sls*, in the hills. Soothly he came against \sls (them)\sls* of \sls (or on)\sls* the contrary part. 
\p  
\v 69 Soothly the espies or ambushments, \sls (that is, men in ambush)\sls*, rose up \sls (out)\sls* of their places, and joined battle. And all that were of Jonathan’s part fled, 
\p  
\v 70 and no man of them was left, no but Mattathias, son of Absalom, and Judas, son of Chalphi, prince\sls (s)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* knighthood and host \sls (or the army)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 71 And Jonathan rent \sls (or tore)\sls* his clothings, and putted earth in \sls (or on)\sls* his head, and prayed. 
\p  
\v 72 And Jonathan \sls (re)\sls*turned again to them into battle, and \sls (al)\sls*together turned them into flight, and fought \sls (them)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 73 And they of his part that fled saw \sls (this)\sls*, and they \sls (re)\sls*turned again to him, and pursued with him till to Kedesh, to their \sls (own)\sls* tents, and fully \add [they]\add* came till thither. 
\p  
\v 74 And there felled down in that day of aliens three thousand of them, and Jonathan \sls (re)\sls*turned again into Jerusalem. 
\c 12  
\cl CHAPTER 12 
\p  
\v 1 And Jonathan saw that the time helped him; and he chose men, and sent them to Rome, for to ordain and renew friendship with them. 
\p  
\v 2 And to \sls (the)\sls* Spartans \sls (or Lacedae-monians)\sls*, and to other places, he sent epistles by \add [or after]\add* the same form. 
\p  
\v 3 And they went to Rome, and entered into the court, and said, Jonathan, highest priest, and the folk of Jews, sent us, for to renew friendship and fellowship, by the former \sls (times)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 4 And they gave to them epistles to them by places, \sls (so)\sls* that they should lead forth them \add [or lead them forth]\add* into the land of Judea with peace. 
\p  
\v 5 And this is the ensample of \sls (the)\sls* epistles, which Jonathan wrote to \sls (the)\sls* Spartans \sls (or to the Lacedaemonians)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 6 Jonathan, \sls (the)\sls* highest priest, and the elder men of the folk, and priests, and other people of Jews, to Spartans \sls (or Lacedaemonians)\sls*, brethren, health. 
\p  
\v 7 Now before epistles were sent to Onias, \sls (the)\sls* highest priest, from Darius, that reigned with you; for ye be our brethren, as the rescript, \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* writing]\add*, containeth, that is under-put. 
\p  
\v 8 And Onias received the man, that was sent, with honour, and took \sls (or received the)\sls* epistles, in which was signified of fellowship and friendship. 
\p  
\v 9 When we had no need of these, and had in comfort \add [or in solace]\add*\sls (the)\sls* holy books that be in our hands, we had rather for to send to you, 
\p  
\v 10 for to renew brotherhood and friendship, lest peradventure we be made aliens from \sls (or to)\sls* you; for why many times passed, since ye sent to us. 
\p  
\v 11 We therefore in all time without ceasing, in solemn days, and others, in which it behooveth, be mindful of you in \sls (the)\sls* sacrifices that we offer, and in observances, as leaveful is \sls (or as it is lawful)\sls*, and beseemeth, for to have had mind of \sls (our)\sls* brethren. 
\p  
\v 12 Therefore we be glad of your glory. 
\p  
\v 13 Forsooth many tribulations and many battles environed us; and kings, that be in our compass, fought against us. 
\p  
\v 14 Therefore we would not be griev-ous to you, neither to other fellows, and our friends, in these battles. 
\p  
\v 15 For we had help of \sls (or from)\sls* heaven, and be delivered, and our enemies be made low. 
\p  
\v 16 Therefore we have chosen Numen-ius, \em the son\em* of Antiochus, and Anti-pater, son of Jason, and sent \sls (them)\sls* to \sls (the)\sls* Romans, for to renew with them both friendship and former fellowship. 
\p  
\v 17 Therefore we commanded to them, that they come also to you, and greet you, and yield to you our epistles of \sls (the)\sls* renewing of our brotherhood. 
\p  
\v 18 And now ye shall do well, answering to us to \add [or of]\add* these things. 
\p  
\v 19 And this is the rescript, \em or \+sls (the)\+sls* again-writing\em*, \sls (or copy)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* epistles, that Oniares \sls (or that Arius)\sls*, the king of \sls (the)\sls* Spartans, sent \sls (to Onias)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 20 Oniares \sls (or Arius)\sls* to Jonathan, great priest, health. \sls (Arius king of the Spartans, or Lacedaemonians, to Onias, the great priest, greetings.)\sls* 
\p  
\v 21 It is found in \sls (the)\sls* writing of \sls (the)\sls* Spartans \sls (or of the Lacedaemonians)\sls*, and of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, that they be brethren, and that they be of the kin of Abraham. 
\p  
\v 22 And now since we know these things, ye do well, writing to us of your peace. 
\p  
\v 23 But and we have again-written to you. Our beasts and our possessions be yours, and yours ours. Therefore we command \sls (our legates)\sls*, for to tell these things to you. 
\p  
\v 24 And \sls (then)\sls* Jonathan heard, that the princes of Demetrius went out with much host, over that \sls (than)\sls* before, for to fight against him. 
\p  
\v 25 And he went out from Jerusalem, and ran against \sls (or met)\sls* them in the country of Hamath; for he gave no space to them, for to enter into his country. 
\p  
\v 26 And he sent espies into \sls (or unto)\sls* the tents of them, and they \sls (re)\sls*turned again, and told \sls (him)\sls*, that they ordained for to come over thither in \sls (the)\sls* night. 
\p  
\v 27 And when the sun had gone down, Jonathan bade his \em men\em*\sls (to)\sls* wake \sls (or to watch)\sls*, and be ready in arms to battle all \sls (the)\sls* night. And he setted keepers by compass of \sls (or about the)\sls* tents; 
\p  
\v 28 and \sls (the)\sls* adversaries heard, that Jonathan was ready with his \em men\em* in battle, and they dreaded, and inwardly were aghast in their heart\sls (s)\sls*, and tended fires in their tents, \em as if they dwelled still in their tents, but they fled privily\em*. 
\p  
\v 29 Forsooth Jonathan, and they that were with him, knew not till to the mor-row; for they saw \sls (the)\sls* lights burning. 
\p  
\v 30 And Jonathan pursued them, and caught not them; for they passed \sls (over)\sls* the flood \sls (or river)\sls* Eleutherus. 
\p  
\v 31 And Jonathan turned to \sls (the)\sls* Arab-ians, that were called Zabadeans; and smote them, and took spoils of them; 
\p  
\v 32 and joined \em in gathering together his host\em*, and came to Damascus, and walked by \sls (or through)\sls* all that country. 
\p  
\v 33 Forsooth Simon went out, and came till to Ascalon, and to the next strengths \sls (or strongholds)\sls*; and he bow-ed down into Joppa, and occupied it. 
\p  
\v 34 For he heard, that they would give \sls (the)\sls* help \sls (or the stronghold)\sls* to \sls (the)\sls* parties of Demetrius; and he putted there keepers, for to keep it. 
\p  
\v 35 And Jonathan \sls (re)\sls*turned again, and called together the elder men of the people, and thought with them for to build strengths \sls (or strongholds)\sls* in Judea, 
\p  
\v 36 and for to build walls in Jerusalem, and for to raise a great height \sls (or a mound)\sls*, betwixt the middle of the high tower and the city, for to part it from the city, \sls (so)\sls* that it were alone, and neither they buy, neither sell, \sls (in it)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 37 And they came together, for to build \sls (up)\sls* the city. And the wall fell down \sls (al)\sls*together, that was on the stream, from the rising of the sun; and he repaired it, that is called Caphenatha. 
\p  
\v 38 And Simon builded Adida in Sephela, and strengthened it, and putted on gates and locks. 
\p  
\v 39 And when Tryphon thought for to reign at \sls (or in)\sls* Asia, and take a diadem, and stretch out \sls (his)\sls* hand into \sls (or upon)\sls* Antiochus \sls (the)\sls* king, 
\p  
\v 40 he dreaded, lest peradventure Jon-athan should not suffer \sls (or allow)\sls* him, but fight against him; and he sought for to catch him, and slay \sls (him)\sls*. And he rose up, and went into Bethshan. 
\p  
\v 41 And Jonathan went out against \em him\em*, with forty thousand of chosen men into battle, and came to Bethshan. 
\p  
\v 42 And Tryphon saw, that Jonathan came with much host, for to stretch out hands into \sls (or against)\sls* him. 
\p  
\v 43 And he dreaded, and received him with honour, and commended him to all his friends; and gave to him gifts, and commanded to his hosts, for to obey to him as to himself. 
\p  
\v 44 And he said to Jonathan, Whereto \sls (or Why)\sls* hast thou travailed all the people, when battle is not to us? 
\p  
\v 45 And now send again them \add [or send them again]\add* into their houses. But choose thou to thee a few men, that be with thee, and come thou with me to Ptolemais, and I shall give it to thee, and other strengths, and host\sls (s)\sls*, \sls (or other strongholds, and armies)\sls*, and all sovereigns of offices; and I shall \sls (re)\sls*turn, and I shall go away. For why therefore I came. 
\p  
\v 46 And he believed to him, and did as he said, and let go the host; and they went away into the land of Judea. 
\p  
\v 47 Forsooth he withheld with him\sls (self)\sls* three thousand of men, of which he sent again into Galilee two thousand; soothly a thousand came with him. 
\p  
\v 48 Forsooth as Jonathan entered into Ptolemais, \sls (the)\sls* men of Ptolemais shutted the gates, and caught \sls (hold of)\sls* him; and slew by \sls (the)\sls* sword, all that entered with him. 
\p  
\v 49 And Tryphon sent \sls (an)\sls* host, and horsemen into Galilee, and into the great field, for to lose \sls (or to destroy)\sls* all the fellows of Jonathan. 
\p  
\v 50 And when they knew that Jonathan was taken, and perished, and all that were with him, they admonished them-selves, and went out ready into battle. 
\p  
\v 51 And they saw that pursued, that thing was to them \sls (to fight)\sls* for the life, and \sls (they)\sls* turned \sls (back)\sls* again. 
\p  
\v 52 Forsooth they came all with peace into the land of Judea. And they bewailed Jonathan greatly, and all that were with him, and Israel mourned with great mourning. 
\p  
\v 53 And all \sls (the)\sls* heathen men that were in the compass of them, sought for to all-break them; for they said, They have no prince and helper; now therefore overcome we them, and take away from men the mind of them. 
\c 13  
\cl CHAPTER 13 
\p  
\v 1 And as Simon heard, that Tryphon \sls (had)\sls* gathered a great host, for to come into the land of Judea, and for to destroy it, 
\p  
\v 2 and saw that the people was in trembling and dread, he went up to Jerusalem, and gathered the people; 
\p  
\v 3 and admonished, and said, Ye know, how great things I, and my brethren, and the house of my father, have done, for \sls (the)\sls* laws, and for holy things \sls (or the Temple)\sls*, \sls (the)\sls* battles, and what manner anguishes we saw. 
\p  
\v 4 For love, \add [or For grace, or cause]\add*, of these things all my brethren perished for Israel, and I alone am left. 
\p  
\v 5 And now befall it not to me, for to spare my \sls (own)\sls* life, \add [or my soul]\add*, in all the time of tribulation; for I am no better than my brethren. 
\p  
\v 6 Therefore I shall avenge my folk, and holy things \sls (or the Temple)\sls*, and our children, and \sls (our)\sls* wives; for all \sls (the)\sls* heathen men be gathered, for to destroy us, because of enmity. 
\p  
\v 7 And the spirit of the people was kindled together, as it \sls (or as they)\sls* heard these words. 
\p  
\v 8 And they answered with \sls (a)\sls* great voice, saying, Thou art our duke instead of Judas, and Jonathan, thy brother\sls (s)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 9 fight thou our battle\sls (s)\sls*, and all things whatever thou shalt say to us, we shall do. 
\p  
\v 10 And he gathered all \sls (the)\sls* men fighters, and hast\sls (en)\sls*ed for to end \sls (or to finish)\sls* all the walls of Jerusalem, and \add [he]\add* strengthened it in compass. 
\p  
\v 11 And he sent Jonathan, the son of Absalom, and with him a new host, into Joppa. And when he had put \add [or cast]\add* out these men that were in it, he dwelt there. 
\p  
\v 12 And Tryphon moved from Ptole-mais, with much host, for to come into the land of Judea, and Jonathan with him in keeping \sls (or his prisoner)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 13 Forsooth Simon applied in Adida \sls (or But Simon encamped at Adida)\sls*, \sls (over)\sls* against the face of the field. 
\p  
\v 14 And as Tryphon knew, that Simon rose \sls (up)\sls*, in the stead \add [or instead]\add* of his brother Jonathan, and that he was to joining battle with him, he sent to him legates \sls (or messengers)\sls*, and said, 
\p  
\v 15 For \sls (the)\sls* silver, that thy brother Jonathan ought \sls (or owed)\sls*, in \sls (the)\sls* accounts of the king, \sls (is the reason that)\sls* we \sls (have)\sls* withheld him. 
\p  
\v 16 And now send thou an hundred talents of silver, and his two sons \sls (as)\sls* pledges \sls (or hostages)\sls*, \sls (so)\sls* that he not dismissed \sls (or released)\sls* flee from us, and we shall again-send him \sls (or let him go)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 17 And Simon knew, that with guile he spake with him. Nevertheless he commanded the silver for to be given, and \sls (the)\sls* children, lest he should take great enmity of the people of Israel, 
\p  
\v 18 saying, For he sent not to him \sls (the)\sls* silver and \sls (the)\sls* children, therefore he \sls (Jonathan)\sls* perished. 
\p  
\v 19 And he sent the children, and an hundred talents. And he \sls (Tryphon)\sls* lied, and dismissed not Jonathan. 
\p  
\v 20 And after these things, Tryphon came within the country, for to destroy it. And they compassed by the way that leadeth to Adora; and Simon and his host walked into each place, whither ever they went. 
\p  
\v 21 Soothly they that were in the high tower, sent legates, or messengers, to Tryphon, for to hasten \sls (himself)\sls* to come by \sls (the)\sls* desert, and send to them foods. 
\p  
\v 22 And Tryphon made ready all the multitude of horsemen, for to come in that night. Soothly there was full much snow, and \sls (so)\sls* he came not \sls (there, but instead went)\sls* into Gilead. 
\p  
\v 23 And when he nighed to Bascama, he slew Jonathan, and his sons, there. 
\p  
\v 24 And \sls (then)\sls* Tryphon \sls (re)\sls*turned, and went into his land. 
\p  
\v 25 And Simon sent, and took the bones of Jonathan, his brother, and buried those in Modin, the city of his fathers. 
\p  
\v 26 And all Israel bewailed him with great wailing, and they bemourned \add [or mourned]\add* him \sls (for)\sls* many days. 
\p  
\v 27 And Simon builded on the sepulchre of his father and his brethren an high building in \sls (or to)\sls* the sight, with stone\sls (s)\sls* polished, \em or fair dighted\em*, \sls (or hewn)\sls*, behind and before. 
\p  
\v 28 And he ordained seven small buildings, \em broad beneath and sharp above\em*, one against one, to \sls (or for his)\sls* father, and mother, and four brethren. 
\p  
\v 29 And to these he putted about great pillars, and on the pillars \sls (their)\sls* armours, to \sls (or for)\sls* everlasting mind; and beside \sls (the)\sls* armours ships engraved \add [or graven ships]\add*, which should be seen of \sls (or by)\sls* men sailing in \sls (or on)\sls* the sea. 
\p  
\v 30 This is the sepulchre that \em Simon\em* made in Modin, \sls (there)\sls* till into this day. 
\p  
\v 31 Forsooth when Tryphon made way with Antiochus, the young king, in guile he slew him, 
\p  
\v 32 and reigned in his stead; and \add [he]\add* putted on him\sls (self)\sls* the diadem of Asia, and made great vengeance in the land. 
\p  
\v 33 And Simon builded \sls (the)\sls* strengths of Judea, and warded them with high towers, and great walls, and gates, and locks; and putted foods in \sls (the)\sls* strengthenings \sls (or the strongholds)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 34 And Simon chose men, and sent to King Demetrius, \sls (so)\sls* that he should make remission \sls (or give forgiveness)\sls* to the country, for all \sls (the)\sls* deeds of Tryphon were done by ravishing. 
\p  
\v 35 And king Demetrius answered to him to \sls (or with)\sls* these words, and wrote such an epistle. 
\p  
\v 36 King Demetrius to Simon, highest priest, and friend of kings, and to the elder men, and folk of Jews, health. 
\p  
\v 37 We received the golden crown, and \sls (the)\sls* baheu, \em that is, an ornament of \+sls (or for)\+sls* the neck, made with gold rings\em*, which ye sent, and be ready for to make with you great peace, and for to write to \sls (the)\sls* provosts of the king, for to release to you what things we forgave; 
\p  
\v 38 for whatever things we ordain to you, be stable. The strengths \sls (or the strongholds)\sls* that ye builded, be to you; 
\p  
\v 39 and we forgive ignorances and sins, till into this day, and the crown that ye ought \sls (or also the crown tax that ye owe us)\sls*; and if any other thing was tributary, \em either bound to tribute\em*, in Jerusalem, now be it not tributary. 
\p  
\v 40 And if any of you be able for to be written together among our men, be they written together, and peace \em be\em* betwixt us. 
\p  
\v 41 In the hundred year and seventieth, the yoke of \sls (the)\sls* heathen men was taken away from Israel. 
\p  
\v 42 And the people began to write in tables \sls (or on tablets)\sls*, and common \add [or open]\add* doings, in the first year under Simon, \sls (the)\sls* highest priest, \sls (the)\sls* great duke, and prince of \sls (the)\sls* Jews. 
\p  
\v 43 In those days Simon applied to \sls (or encamped at)\sls* Gazara, and environed it with tents, \em either men of arms\em*, \sls (\+em or with armed men\+em*)\sls*, and made engines, and applied \sls (or set them close)\sls* to the city, and smote one tower, and took it. 
\p  
\v 44 And they that brake out, were within the engine in the city, and \sls (then a)\sls* great stirring was made in the city. 
\p  
\v 45 And they went up, that were in the city, with their wives, and sons, on the wall\sls (s)\sls*, with their coats cut, and cried with \sls (a)\sls* great voice, asking of Simon that right hands be given to them, 
\p  
\v 46 and said, Yield thou not to us by \add [or after]\add* our malices, but by \add [or after]\add* thy mercies, and we shall serve to thee. 
\p  
\v 47 And Simon was bowed, \em either folded\em*, and fought not against them; nevertheless he casted them out of the city, and cleansed fully the houses in which were simulacra \sls (or idols)\sls*, and then he entered into it with hymns, and blessed the Lord \add [or blessing the Lord]\add*. 
\p  
\v 48 And when all uncleanness was cast out thereof, he setted therein men, that should do the law; and he strengthened it, and made an habitation to him\sls (self)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 49 Forsooth they that were in the high tower of Jerusalem, were forbid-den for to go out and go in, into the country, and buy, and sell; and they hungered greatly, and many of them perished for hunger. 
\p  
\v 50 And they cried to Simon, for to take right hands, and he gave \sls (it)\sls* to them; and he casted out them from thence, and cleansed the high tower from defoulings \sls (or defilings)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 51 And they entered into it in the three and twentieth day of the second month, in the hundred and one and seventy year, with praising, and branches of palms, and instruments of music, \em either gitterns\em*, \sls (\+em or citherns\+em*)\sls*, and cymbals, and harps, \add [or psalteries]\add*, and hymns, and songs, for the great enemy of Israel was all-broken. 
\p  
\v 52 And he ordained, that in all years these days should be done with glad-ness. And he strengthened the hill of the temple, that was beside the high tower, and dwelt there, he, and they that were with him. 
\p  
\v 53 And Simon saw John, his son, that he was a man of battle, and he putted him duke \sls (or leader)\sls* of all virtues, \em that is, warriors\em*, and he dwelt in Gazara. 
\c 14  
\cl CHAPTER 14 
\p  
\v 1 In the hundred and two and seventy \add [or seventieth]\add* year, king Demetrius gathered his host, and went to Media, for to draw together helps to him\sls (self)\sls*, for to overcome Tryphon. 
\p  
\v 2 And as Arsaces, king of Persia and Media, heard that Demetrius entered into his nigh coasts, he sent one of his princes, for to take him quick, and that he should bring him to himself. 
\p  
\v 3 And he went, and smote the host of Demetrius, and took him, and led him to Arsaces, and he putted him into keeping \sls (or into prison)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 4 And the land of Judea was still, \em either peaceable\em*, in all the days of Simon, and he sought good things of \sls (or for)\sls* his folk; and his power and his glory pleased them in all days. 
\p  
\v 5 And with all his glory he took Joppa into haven, and made entry into \sls (the)\sls* isles of the sea; 
\p  
\v 6 and alarged \sls (or enlarged)\sls* the coasts of his people, and wielded the country. 
\p  
\v 7 And he gathered much captivity, and was lord in Gazara, and Beth-sura, and the high tower; and he did away \sls (the)\sls* uncleannesses of it, and there was not that against-stood him. 
\p  
\v 8 And each man tilled his own land in peace, and the land of Judea gave his \sls (or its)\sls* fruits, and \sls (the)\sls* trees of \sls (the)\sls* fields their fruit. 
\p  
\v 9 \sls (The)\sls* Elder men sat all in \sls (the)\sls* streets, and treated of \sls (the)\sls* goods of the land; and young men clothed them-\sls (selves)\sls* in glory, and stoles of battle, \em that is armours, in the time of peace\em*. 
\p  
\v 10 And to the cities he gave foods, and ordained those \add [or them]\add*, that those \add [or they]\add* were vessels of strengthening, till that the name of his glory was named till to the last of \sls (the)\sls* earth. 
\p  
\v 11 He made peace on the land, and Israel was glad with great gladness; 
\p  
\v 12 and each man sat under his vine, and under his fig tree, neither there was that feared them \sls (or made them afraid)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 13 The fighting man against them failed on \sls (the)\sls* earth; \sls (the)\sls* kings were all-broken in those days. 
\p  
\v 14 And he confirmed all meek men of his people, and he sought out the law, and did away all evil and wickedness; 
\p  
\v 15 and he glorified holy things, and multiplied vessels of holy things. \sls (and he beautified the Temple, and multi-plied the vessels of the Temple.)\sls* 
\p  
\v 16 And it was heard at Rome, that Jonathan was dead, and till into \sls (the)\sls* Spartans, and they were full sorrowful. 
\p  
\v 17 Forsooth as they heard, that Simon, his brother, was made highest priest in his stead, and he wielded the country, and \sls (the)\sls* cities in it, 
\p  
\v 18 they wrote to him in brazen tables \sls (or on brass or bronze tablets)\sls*, for to renew \sls (the)\sls* friendship, and fellowship, that they made with Judas and Jonathan, his brethren; 
\p  
\v 19 and they were read in the sight of the church \sls (or the congregation)\sls* in Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 20 And this \em is\em* the ensample \sls (or a copy)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* epistles, that \sls (the)\sls* Spartans \sls (or Lacedaemonians)\sls* sent. The prince and the cities, \em that is, \+sls (the)\+sls* governors of the cities\em*, of \sls (the)\sls* Spartans to Simon, \sls (the)\sls* great priest, and to the elder men, and priests, and to \sls (the)\sls* other people of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, brethren, health. 
\p  
\v 21 \sls (The)\sls* Legates that were sent to our people, told to us of your glory, and honour, and gladness, and we joyed in \sls (or at)\sls* the entry of them. 
\p  
\v 22 And we have written what things were said of them in \sls (the)\sls* councils \add [or in \+sls (the)\+sls* council]\add* of \sls (the)\sls* people, thus. Numenius, \em the son\em* of Antiochus, and Antipater, the son of Jason, \sls (the)\sls* legates of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, came to us, and renewed with us the former friendship. 
\p  
\v 23 And it pleased to the people, for to receive the men gloriously, and to put \sls (an)\sls* ensample of their words in departed books of the people \sls (or and to put a copy of their address in the public records)\sls*, that it be to mind to the people of \sls (the)\sls* Spartans \sls (or so that it be remembered by the Lacedaemon-ians)\sls*; forsooth we have written \sls (an)\sls* ensample \sls (or a copy)\sls* of these things to Simon, the great priest. 
\p  
\v 24 Forsooth after these things, Simon sent Numenius to Rome, having a great golden shield, in \sls (the)\sls* weight of a thousand bezants, for to ordain fellowship with them. 
\p  
\v 25 Soothly when the people of Rome heard these words, they said, What doing of thankings shall we yield to Simon, and his sons? 
\p  
\v 26 For he restored his brethren, and overcame the enemies of Israel from them. And they ordained to him liberty \add [or they ordained to them \+sls (their)\+sls* liberty]\add*, 
\p  
\v 27 and wrote \sls (it)\sls* in brazen tables \sls (or on brass or bronze tablets)\sls*, and \sls (the)\sls*\em Jews\em* putted in titles \sls (or on pillars)\sls*, in the mount of Zion. And this is \sls (an)\sls* en-sample \sls (or a copy)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* writing. In the eighteenth day of the month Elul, \em that is, August\em*, in the hundred and two and seventy \add [or seventieth]\add* year, the third year under Simon, \sls (the)\sls* great priest, 
\p  
\v 28 in Saramel, in the great coming together of \sls (the)\sls* priests, \sls (and)\sls* of the people, and \sls (the)\sls* princes, and \sls (the)\sls* folk, and the elder men \add [or seniors]\add* of the country, these things were made known; 
\p  
\v 29 for many times battles were done \add [or be made]\add* in your country. Forsooth Simon, the son of Mattathias, of the sons of Jarib, and his brethren, gave themselves to peril, and against-stood \sls (the)\sls* adversaries of their folk, \sls (so)\sls* that their holy things \sls (or their Temple)\sls* and \sls (the)\sls* law should stand; and by great glory they glorified their folk \sls (or they brought great glory to their people)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 30 And Jonathan gathered his folk \sls (together)\sls*, and was made to them a great priest, and is put to his people. 
\p  
\v 31 And the enemies of them would defoul holy things \sls (or defile the Temple)\sls*, and destroy the country of them, and stretch forth hands into holy things of them \sls (or upon their Temple)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 32 Then Simon against-stood, and fought for his people, and gave many riches \add [or much money]\add*, and armed \sls (the)\sls* men of virtue of his folk, and gave to them solds \sls (or wages)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 33 and strengthened the cities of Judea, and Bethsura, that was in the ends of Judea, where before were \sls (the)\sls* armours of \sls (the)\sls* enemies, and he put-ted there \sls (a)\sls* help, \add [or \+sls (a)\+sls* strength]\add*, \sls (\+em or a stronghold\+em*)\sls*, \sls (with)\sls* men of \sls (the)\sls* Jews. 
\p  
\v 34 And he strengthened Joppa, that was at the sea, and Gazara, that was in the coasts of Azotus, in which \sls (the)\sls* enemies \sls (had)\sls* dwelt before; and he setted there Jews, and whatever things were able to \sls (the)\sls* amending of them, he putted in them. 
\p  
\v 35 And the people saw the doing of Simon, and \sls (the)\sls* glory that he thought for to do to his folk, and they made him their duke, and prince of priests, for that he had done all these things, and rightwiseness, and faith that he kept to his folk; and he sought out in all manner for to raise \sls (up)\sls* his people. 
\p  
\v 36 And in his days it had prosperity in his hands, \sls (so)\sls* that heathen men were taken away from the country of them, \sls (and)\sls* which were \sls (also)\sls* in the city of David in Jerusalem, in the high tower, from which they came out, and defouled all things that were in compass of holy things \sls (or around the Temple)\sls*, and gave great wound to \sls (its)\sls* chastity \sls (or its purity)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 37 And he setted therein men Jews, to defending of the country, and \sls (the)\sls* city, and raised \sls (up)\sls* the walls in \sls (or of)\sls* Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 38 And king Demetrius ordained to him the highest priesthood; 
\p  
\v 39 by this he made him his friend, and glorified him in great glory. 
\p  
\v 40 For he heard, that \sls (the)\sls* Jews were called of \sls (or by the)\sls* Romans \sls (their)\sls* friends, and fellows, and brethren, and that they received \sls (the)\sls* legates \sls (or the ambassadors)\sls* of Simon gloriously; 
\p  
\v 41 and that \sls (the)\sls* Jews, and \sls (the)\sls* priests of them, consented, him for to be their duke, and highest priest \add [into]\add* without end, till there rise a faithful prophet; 
\p  
\v 42 and that he be duke on them, and care, \em or busyness\em*, were to him for \sls (the)\sls* holy things; and that he should ordain governors \add [or provosts]\add* on the works of them, and on the country, and on arms, and on strengths \sls (or strongholds)\sls*; and care be to him of \sls (the)\sls* holy things \sls (or the Temple)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 43 and that he be heard of \sls (or obey-ed by all)\sls* men, and all \sls (the)\sls* writings in the country be written together under the name of him, and that he be covered with purple and gold; 
\p  
\v 44 and that it be not leaveful to \sls (or lawful for)\sls* any of the people, and to priests, for to make anything of these void, and against-say \sls (or gainsay)\sls* to these things that be said of him, either for to call together \sls (a)\sls* covent, or convent, \sls (or an assembly)\sls* in the country without him; and for to be clothed in purple, and for to use a golden lace, or \sls (an)\sls* ouch \sls (or clasp)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 45 Soothly he that shall do without this, either \add [or]\add* shall make void any of these \sls (things)\sls*, shall be guilty. 
\p  
\v 46 And \sls (so)\sls* it pleased \sls (al)\sls*together to all the people, for to ordain Simon, and do by \add [or after]\add* these words. 
\p  
\v 47 And Simon received \sls (this)\sls*, and it pleased him, that he should use \add [or that he was set in]\add*\sls (the)\sls* high priesthood or \sls (the)\sls* highest priesthood, and be duke and prince of the folk of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, and priests, and be the sovereign of all men. 
\p  
\v 48 And they ordained for to put this writing in brazen tables \sls (or on brass tablets)\sls*, and put them in the wall about the compassing \add [or the walking place]\add* of \sls (the)\sls* holy things \sls (or the Temple precincts)\sls*, in \sls (a)\sls* solemn place; 
\p  
\v 49 forsooth for to put \sls (an)\sls* ensample \sls (or copy)\sls* of these in the treasury, \sls (so)\sls* that Simon have \sls (them)\sls* and his sons. 
\c 15  
\cl CHAPTER 15 
\p  
\v 1 And king Antiochus, the son of Demetrius, sent epistles from \sls (the)\sls* isles of the sea to Simon, the priest, and prince of the folk of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, and to all the folk; 
\p  
\v 2 and those were containing this manner \sls (or contents)\sls*. King Antiochus to Simon, \sls (the)\sls* great priest, and to the folk of \sls (the)\sls* Jews, health. 
\p  
\v 3 For \sls (as)\sls* some men bearing pestilence wielded the realm of our fathers, forsooth I will challenge the realm, and restore it, as it was before; I made a chosen multitude of host, and I made ships of war. 
\p  
\v 4 Forsooth I will go forth by coun-tries, \sls (so)\sls* that I do vengeance on them that destroyed our country, and that made many cities desolate in my realm. 
\p  
\v 5 Now therefore I ordain, \em either confirm\em*, to thee all offerings, that kings before me forgave to thee, and what-ever other gifts they forgave to thee; 
\p  
\v 6 and I suffer \sls (or allow)\sls* thee for to make print, or smiting, of thine own money, in thy region, \em or country\em*. 
\p  
\v 7 Soothly \em I suffer\em* Jerusalem for to be holy and free \sls (or \+em I allow\+em* Jerusalem and the Temple to be free)\sls*, and all arms that be made, and strengths \sls (or strongholds)\sls*, that thou hast made out, and that thou holdest, dwell to thee; 
\p  
\v 8 and all debt of \sls (or owing to)\sls* the king, and those that be to coming of \sls (the)\sls* king’s things, from this time and into all-time be forgiven to thee. 
\p  
\v 9 Soothly when we shall wield our realm, we shall glorify thee, and thy folk, and temple, with great glory, so that your glory be showed in all earth. 
\p  
\v 10 In the hundred year and four and seventieth year Antiochus went out into the land of his fathers, and all \sls (the)\sls* hosts came together to him, so that few were left with Tryphon. 
\p  
\v 11 And king Antiochus pursued him, and \em Tryphon\em* came into Dora, and fled \add [or fleeing]\add* by the sea coast; 
\p  
\v 12 for he knew, that evils were gathered on him, and \sls (that)\sls* the host forsook him. 
\p  
\v 13 And Antiochus applied on \sls (or encamped at)\sls* Dora, with sixscore thousand of fighting men, and eight thousand of horsemen; 
\p  
\v 14 and he compassed the city, and ships came from the sea; and they travailed the city by land and \sls (by)\sls* sea, and suffered \sls (or allowed)\sls* no man for to enter, either \add [or]\add* go out. 
\p  
\v 15 Forsooth Numenius came, and they that were with him, from Rome, and had epistles written to \sls (the)\sls* kings and countries, in which these things were contained. 
\p  
\v 16 Lucius, consul, \em or chief governor\em*, of Romans, to king Ptolemy, health. 
\p  
\v 17 Legates, \em either messengers\em*, of Jews came to us, \sls (who be)\sls* our friends, renewing the former friendship and fellowship, sent of \sls (or from)\sls* Simon, prince of priests, and people of Jews. 
\p  
\v 18 Soothly they brought also a golden shield of a thousand bezants. 
\p  
\v 19 Therefore it pleased to us for to write to \sls (the)\sls* kings and countries, that they do not \sls (do)\sls* evils to them, neither impugn them, and their cities, and their countries, and that they bear not help to men fighting against them. 
\p  
\v 20 Forsooth it is seen to us, for to receive of \sls (or from)\sls* them the shield. 
\p  
\v 21 Therefore if any men of pestilence shall flee from the country of them to you, betake ye them to Simon, \sls (the)\sls* prince of priests, \sls (so)\sls* that he do vengeance on them by \add [or after]\add* his law. 
\p  
\v 22 These same things be written to king Demetrius, and Attalus, and Ariarathes, and Arsaces, 
\p  
\v 23 and into all \sls (the)\sls* countries, and \sls (to)\sls* Sampsames, and Spartans, and Delus, and Myndus, and Sicyon, and Caria, and Samos, and Pamphylia, and Lycia, and Halicarnassus, and Rhodes, and Aradus \sls (or Phaselis)\sls*, and Cos, and Side, and Aradus, and Gortyna, and Cnidus, and Cyprus, and Cyrene. 
\p  
\v 24 Forsooth they have written \sls (an)\sls* ensample of these to Simon, prince of priests, and to the people of \sls (the)\sls* Jews. 
\p  
\v 25 Forsooth Antiochus, the king, applied tents in \sls (or encamped at)\sls* Dora the second time, moving to it evermore hands, and making engines; and he closed \sls (up)\sls*\sls (al)\sls*together Tryphon, lest he went out. 
\p  
\v 26 And Simon sent to him two thousand of chosen men, into help, and silver, and gold, and plenteous vessels; 
\p  
\v 27 and he would not take those. But he brake all things that he covenanted with him before, and alienated himself from him. 
\p  
\v 28 And he sent to him Athenobius, one of his friends, for to treat with him, and said, Ye hold Joppa, and Gazara, and the high tower that is in Jerusalem, cities of my realm; 
\p  
\v 29 ye have wasted the coasts of them, and have done great destroying in the land, and without \sls (or through-out)\sls* the coasts of Judea ye be lords by many places in my realm. 
\p  
\v 30 Now therefore give ye the cities, which ye occupied, and \sls (the)\sls* tributes of places, of which ye be lords, out of \sls (the)\sls* ends of Judea. 
\p  
\v 31 Either \add [Or]\add* else give ye for them five hundred talents of silver, and of \sls (the)\sls* destroying that ye have destroyed, and of \sls (the)\sls* tributes of cities, \sls (an)\sls*other five hundred talents; either \add [or]\add* else we shall come, and overcome you. 
\p  
\v 32 And Athenobius, \sls (the)\sls* friend of the king, came into Jerusalem, and saw the glory of Simon, and clearness, in gold, and silver, and plenteous apparel, and was astonished; and \add [he]\add* told to him the words of the king. 
\p  
\v 33 And Simon answered, and said to him, Neither we took alien land, neither withheld other men’s things, but heri-tage of our fathers, that was wielded sometime unjustly of our enemies. 
\p  
\v 34 Soothly we have time, and challenge the heritage of our fathers. 
\p  
\v 35 For why of Joppa and Gazara that thou askest, they did great vengeance in our people, and \add [in our]\add* country; of these we \sls (shall)\sls* give an hundred talents. And Athenobius answered not a word. 
\p  
\v 36 Soothly he \sls (re)\sls*turned again with wrath to the king, and told again to him these words, and the glory of Simon, and all things that he saw. And the king was wroth with great wrath. 
\p  
\v 37 Forsooth Tryphon flew \sls (or fled)\sls* by ship into Orthosia. 
\p  
\v 38 And the king ordained Cendebeus, duke of the sea coast, and gave to him \sls (an)\sls* host of footmen and horsemen; 
\p  
\v 39 and commanded him for to move \sls (his)\sls* tents against \sls (or towards)\sls* the face of Judah; and commanded him for to \sls (re)\sls*build Kedron, and stop the gates of the city, and overcome the people; forsooth the king pursued Tryphon. 
\p  
\v 40 And Cendebeus came to Jamnia, and began for to stir the people to wrath, and for to defoul Judea, and make the people captive, and slay \sls (them)\sls*, 
\p  
\v 41 and \sls (to)\sls*\sls (re)\sls*build Kedron. And he setted there horsemen and \sls (a)\sls* host, \sls (so)\sls* that they should go out, and should walk by \sls (the)\sls* way\sls (s)\sls* of Judea, as the king ordained to him. 
\c 16  
\cl CHAPTER 16 
\p  
\v 1 And John ascended or went up from Gazara, and told to Simon, his father, what things Cendebeus did in \sls (or to)\sls* the people of them. 
\p  
\v 2 And Simon called his twain elder sons, Judah and John, and said to them, I, and my brethren, and the house of my father, have overcome the enemies of Israel, from youth till into this day; and it had prosperity in our hands, for to deliver Israel sometimes. 
\p  
\v 3 Forsooth now I have elded, \add [or olded]\add*, \sls (or gotten old)\sls*, but be ye in my stead, and of my brother, and go ye out, and fight for our folk; forsooth \sls (the)\sls* help of heaven be with you. 
\p  
\v 4 And he chose \sls (out)\sls* of the country twenty thousand of fighting men, and horsemen; and they went out to \sls (or against)\sls* Cendebeus, and slept in Modin. 
\p  
\v 5 And they rose early, and went into the field, and lo! a copious host \em came\em* into the meeting of them, of footmen and horsemen; and a running flood \sls (or river)\sls* was betwixt the midst of them. 
\p  
\v 6 And he and his people moved the battle array \add [or the tents]\add*\sls (over)\sls* against the face of them, \sls (or opposite them)\sls*, and he saw the people trembling to pass over the stream of water, and he passed over the first; and \sls (the)\sls* men saw him, and passed \sls (over)\sls* after him. 
\p  
\v 7 And he parted the people, and horsemen in the middle of footmen; forsooth the multitude of horsemen of \sls (the)\sls* adversaries was full plenteous. 
\p  
\v 8 And they cried on high with \sls (the)\sls* holy trumps; and Cendebeus was turned into flight, and his host, and many of them fell wounded; soothly the residues fled into \sls (the)\sls* strength. 
\p  
\v 9 Then Judas, the brother of John, was wounded; forsooth John pursued them, till \em Cendebeus\em* came to Kedron, which he \sls (had)\sls* builded \sls (again)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 10 And they fled till to \sls (the)\sls* towers, that were in the fields of Azotus, and he burnt them with fire; and there fell of them two thousand of men, and he \sls (re)\sls*turned again into Judea in peace. 
\p  
\v 11 And Ptolemy \sls (or Ptolemeus)\sls*, the son of Abubus, was ordained duke in the field of Jericho, and \add [he]\add* had much silver and gold; 
\p  
\v 12 for he wedded the daughter of the highest priest. 
\p  
\v 13 And the heart of him was raised \sls (up)\sls*, and he would wield the country; and he thought guile against Simon and his sons, for to do away them. 
\p  
\v 14 Forsooth Simon walked by \sls (the)\sls* cities that were in the country of Judea, and bare busyness of them, and came down into Jericho, he, and Mattathias, his son, and Judas, in the hundred year and seven and seventieth, in the eleventh month; this is the month of Shebat, \em that is, January-February\em*. 
\p  
\v 15 And \sls (Ptolemy)\sls* the son of Abubus, received them into a little strength, that is called Docus, with guile, which he \sls (had)\sls* builded; and made to them a great feast, and hid men there. 
\p  
\v 16 And when Simon was full of drink, and his sons, Ptolemy rose with his \em men\em*, and took their arms, and entered into the feast, and slew him, and his two sons, and some children of him. 
\p  
\v 17 And he did a great deceit in Israel, and yielded evils for goods. 
\p  
\v 18 And Ptolemy wrote these things, and sent to the king, for to send to him an host into help, and he should \sls (or would)\sls* betake to him the country and \sls (the)\sls* cities of them, and tributes. 
\p  
\v 19 And he sent others into Gazara, for to do away John; and to the tribunes he sent epistles, that they should come to him, and he should give to them silver, and gold, and gifts. 
\p  
\v 20 And he sent other men, for to occupy Jerusalem, and the mount of the temple. 
\p  
\v 21 And some man ran before, and told to John in Gazara, that his father perished, and his brethren, and that he, \sls (Ptolemy)\sls*, sent that thou also be slain. 
\p  
\v 22 Forsooth as he heard, he wonder-ed \add [or dreaded]\add* greatly; and he caught the men that came to lose \sls (or destroy)\sls* him, and he slew them; for he knew, that they sought for to lose him. 
\p  
\v 23 And other things of John’s words, and of his battles, and good virtues, in which he did strongly, and of \sls (the)\sls* building of walls, which he fully made, and of things done of \sls (or by)\sls* him, 
\p  
\v 24 lo! these be written in the book of days of his priesthood, since he was made prince of priests after his father. 